=begin
  InquiConundrum.lic

  Automates the Zephyra Wilds Conundrum - the "repair the clockwerke
  orangutan" timed minigame (Mistwarden Temple / Zephyra Wilds). Waits idle
  until you are put anywhere with "Mistwarden Temple" or "Zephyra Wilds" in
  the room title - not necessarily the guide's own room - then starts
  working immediately:
  logging parts, clearing traps/vines/wards, and exploring. It re-anchors its
  navigation onto the guide's actual room as soon as exploration finds it,
  listens for the floating spherical guide's piece announcements, kicks
  matched pieces back to the guide room one at a time, and resets itself
  to wait for the next run when the event ends. Stays running across many
  back-to-back runs until you stop it.

  Usage:
    ;inquiconundrum                  - always run this way, no inline options
    ;inquiconundrum set               - show current options
    ;inquiconundrum set destroytraps=true debug=true
    ;inquiconundrum help              - show usage and options

  Hostiles are never fought during plain exploration - monsters out there
  don't attack and can't be attacked anyway. Combat is only ever this
  script's problem when a kick is rejected as "too dangerous" while
  actively pushing a found piece home; that's the one and only time it
  literally pauses itself (pause_script) and announces it. Kill whatever's
  blocking the kick, then resume with ;unpause inquiconundrum. Blocked
  plain movement (traps, etc.) is never paused for - it's just retried
  quietly until it succeeds.

 author: Kyrandos
  other Scripts: Loresang, VolnRestore2, Merchantical
  game: gs
  tags: conundrum, Zephyra wilds, inquisition, minigame
  version: 1.27.0
  required: Lich > 5.0; go2.lic (mapdb required - ;repository download-mapdb)
  \\Version\\
			1.0.0 6/21/2026 - initial release
      1.1.0 6/25/2026 - Logic improvements, multiplayer added
=end

module InquiConundrum
  # Raised by check_for_available_piece! to unwind out of however deep
  # continue_exploration's recursion (explore_exit/explore_new_exits) has
  # gotten, back to tick's single rescue point - a piece becoming :located
  # mid-exploration takes priority over finishing whatever exploration step
  # was in progress. Not a real error - never propagates past tick.
  class PieceBecameAvailable < StandardError; end

  # Raised by check_for_run_end! the moment the run is actually over.
  # Confirmed in the field: a surrendermania ejection landing mid-move got
  # misread by wait_for_room_arrival's generic "a room description just
  # arrived" check as the arrival confirmation for whatever direction
  # explore_exit was busy walking - it recorded a bogus edge into the
  # ejection room (which doesn't connect to anything) and kept trying to
  # explore exits from there ("You can't go there" forever), since tick
  # only checks maybe_end_run once, at its own top, and never got back
  # around to it. This unwinds the same way PieceBecameAvailable does -
  # straight back to tick's rescue - so maybe_end_run gets a fresh look on
  # the very next tick instead of waiting for an action that may never
  # actually finish.
  class RunEnding < StandardError; end

  # Raised by move() the moment it's been retrying the exact same failing
  # direction for too long. Confirmed in the field: continue_exploration's
  # backtrack step (move(@parent[uid][:back])) trusts that the reverse of
  # whatever direction got us into a room is always a working way back out
  # - this maze has confirmed non-reciprocal passages (see explore_new_
  # exits' own comment on the same risk), so that assumption can be wrong,
  # and move's own retry-forever loop had no escape from it at all. Stood
  # there repeating "n"/"You can't go there" while a monster wandered in
  # and killed it. Unwinds the same way PieceBecameAvailable/RunEnding do -
  # straight back to tick's rescue, which re-runs tick's own top-level
  # dispatch fresh on the next call (transporting a known piece? something
  # located? more to explore? an obstacle to clear?) instead of staying
  # wedged on whatever specific move was never going to succeed. Carries
  # uid/direction so tick's rescue can also invalidate @parent[uid][:back]
  # when that's specifically what got stuck - otherwise the very next
  # continue_exploration call at the same room would just retry the exact
  # same doomed backtrack and raise this all over again every cycle.
  class StuckMove < StandardError
    attr_reader :uid, :direction

    def initialize(message, uid:, direction:)
      super(message)
      @uid = uid
      @direction = direction
    end
  end

  PIECE_DESCRIPTOR_REGEX = /\b((?:[a-z]+ ){1,3}(?:gear|screw|lever|cog|spring))\b/i
  VINE_REGEX             = /tangle of .*?vines|vine-tangled/i
  # Confirmed in the field: a vine-tangled solid rock wall phrased its
  # direction as "blocking the path north" - not "covering the passage
  # north" like an actual tangle of vines does - so this missed it
  # entirely (every directional lookup for that exact obstacle silently
  # came back nil, including attempt_move's own obstacle-destroy check,
  # which is how a return-trip move ended up retrying "you can't go
  # there" against a wall that was still standing, and how the room
  # behind it - piece included - went permanently unreachable without
  # ever being recognized as blocked at all). Matches either wording now.
  VINE_DIRECTION_REGEX   = /(?:covering|blocking) the (?:path|passage) (north|south|east|west|northeast|northwest|southeast|southwest|up|down|out)/i
  WARD_REGEX             = /thornbound ward/i
  WARD_DIRECTION_REGEX   = /blocking the (?:path|passage) (north|south|east|west|northeast|northwest|southeast|southwest|up|down|out)/i
  TRAP_REGEX             = /formation of smooth bone spikes|twisting coral tendrils/i
  MOSS_REGEX             = /slippery moss/i
  # Not a TRAP_REGEX hazard - killing it doesn't help. Same deal as
  # slippery moss: kneel and crawl through instead of walking it off.
  MUSHROOM_REGEX         = /formation of large mushrooms/i

  ANNOUNCE_REGEX    = /floating spherical guide say in the back of your mind.*?Please fetch (?:a|an) (.+?) at your earliest/i
  DELIVERY_REGEX    = /(?:A|An) (.+?) has been brought to the orangutan\./i
  COMPLETE_REGEX    = /we know all the components needed/i
  TIME_WARNING_REGEX = /(\d+) minutes? (?:remain|left)|almost out of time/i

  # Only matters with surrendermania on - once the guide says this, surrender
  # twice and treat the run as over (it is, even though we're never moved to
  # END_ROOM_REGEX's room for it).
  SURRENDER_THRESHOLD_REGEX = /floating spherical guide say in the back of your mind.*?passed the threshold for winning a prize if you surrender/i

  # "ask guide about status" answers with a header line, then each still-needed
  # piece on its own line ("A colossal bronze spring"), until a blank line or
  # an unrelated sentence ends the list.
  STATUS_HEADER_REGEX = /you still need to bring the following pieces/i
  STATUS_ITEM_REGEX   = /^(?:A|An) ((?:[a-z]+ ){1,3}(?:gear|screw|lever|cog|spring))\.?\s*$/i

  # ZONE_REGEX is deliberately broader than START_ROOM_REGEX: the character
  # can be dropped in anywhere in the zone when the event starts, not just
  # the guide's own room. We start working immediately on zone entry and
  # treat wherever we happen to be as a provisional anchor, then re-root
  # onto the guide's actual room once exploration finds it (see
  # reroot_tree).
  ZONE_REGEX       = /Mistwarden Temple|Zephyra Wilds/i
  START_ROOM_REGEX = /Mistwarden Temple, Inner Shrine/i
  END_ROOM_REGEX   = /Testing Module Exit/i

  MAX_RUN_SECONDS = 31 * 60
  STATUS_UPDATE_INTERVAL_SECONDS = 30 # how often the idle status summary reprints

  # Room id of the Arena Magister who grants entry, for go2 to walk back to
  # from the post-ejection room. Only used when repeatevent is on.
  ARENA_MAGISTER_UID = '36701'.freeze
  GO2_TIMEOUT_SECONDS = 5 * 60

  # Fixed entry-point room id a fresh event instance always drops you into
  # (unlike the maze rooms themselves, which get regenerated per run). A
  # follower has no business fighting anything while being dragged along
  # mid-regroup/mid-requeue - inky.lic gets paused for the whole stretch
  # and only unpaused once this room confirms the new run has actually
  # started.
  NEW_EVENT_START_ROOM_UID = '8401129'.freeze
  INKY_SCRIPT = 'inky'.freeze

  # Grouped + repeatevent: how long the leader waits, after stowing/girding,
  # for followers to "join" them before heading back to the arena anyway.
  # Followers themselves never wait on a timer here at all - they only ever
  # join and then ride along with whatever the leader does (see
  # regroup_with_leader_then_return_to_arena) - wait_for_new_event_then_
  # unpause_inky's own GO2_TIMEOUT_SECONDS deadline is their only safety net.
  REGROUP_TIMEOUT_SECONDS = 30

  OPTION_KEYS = [:destroytraps, :debug, :repeatevent, :surrendermania, :pacifist].freeze
  OPTION_DEFAULTS = { destroytraps: false, debug: false, repeatevent: false, surrendermania: false, pacifist: false }.freeze

  # pacifist: confirmed in the field - resorting to violence the moment the
  # only one or two announced pieces happen to be monster-blocked is too
  # eager when there's still plenty of unexplored map and unlogged
  # obstacles to work through instead, which would likely turn up an
  # unblocked piece anyway. Only force combat once at least this many
  # pieces have been announced (so "every located piece is blocked" means
  # something) - below that, next_located_descriptor just returns nil and
  # lets exploration/obstacle-clearing run instead, same as if nothing
  # were located at all.
  PACIFIST_FORCE_MIN_ANNOUNCED = 4

  # pacifist: a monster that blocked a piece doesn't necessarily stay
  # there forever - wanders off, dies to something else, etc. Re-eligible
  # for a normal (non-forced) pickup attempt once this long has passed
  # since it was last abandoned. check_for_available_piece! only lets a
  # piece with any history in @blocked_pieces (still within its retry
  # window via @forced_piece, or past it) interrupt exploration/obstacle-
  # clearing if it's actually closer to the guide than wherever we
  # currently are - a fresh, never-blocked piece still always interrupts
  # unconditionally. maybe_abandon_for_closer_piece applies that same
  # distance check to an active return-part job too.
  PACIFIST_BLOCKED_RETRY_SECONDS = 1 * 60

  # "Claimed by another player" (continue_transport's GameObj.pcs.any?
  # check - some other player physically standing in the room with the
  # piece) was confirmed in the field to be permanent for the rest of the
  # run, with nothing ever rechecking it: that other player might just
  # have been passing through, fighting a monster, or have already left
  # by the time we'd come back - not necessarily still pushing the piece
  # at all. A run was observed delivering 0 pieces despite logging 150+
  # parts, ending in a "all pieces claimed by another player" idle stall
  # because every currently-announced piece got marked :claimed once and
  # never revisited. Same retry-window pattern as @blocked_pieces above -
  # recheck_stale_claims! flips a :claimed piece back to :located once
  # this long has passed since it was marked, so it becomes a normal
  # pickup candidate again instead of being abandoned forever. Acts as the
  # ultimate backstop when group sync can't tell us anything more precise
  # (solo play, or sync data unavailable for some reason) - whenever group
  # sync IS available, CLAIMED_GROUP_SYNC_GRACE_SECONDS below recovers a
  # stale claim far sooner than this.
  CLAIMED_RETRY_SECONDS = 3 * 60
  # group_sync: every player who can physically be in this zone is a
  # teammate also running this same script (confirmed - no random/untracked
  # players are ever possible here), so a teammate's own published claim
  # (current_claim_snapshot, merged into @remote_claims) is authoritative
  # for "is anyone actually still working this piece" - no need to wait out
  # the full CLAIMED_RETRY_SECONDS once that says no. Still wait this short
  # grace period after we first mark something :claimed before trusting an
  # absent remote claim, purely to cover the gap between physically seeing
  # the other character in the room and their own next sync publish
  # actually landing in our merge - not a real "are they still working it"
  # signal on its own.
  CLAIMED_GROUP_SYNC_GRACE_SECONDS = 15

  # Only worth resweeping the known map for missed obstacles (see
  # resweep_for_missed_obstacles!) this often - if nothing's changed since
  # the last sweep, walking the whole map again won't find anything new
  # either.
  RESWEEP_COOLDOWN_SECONDS = 5 * 60

  # move() gives up and raises StuckMove after retrying the same direction
  # for this long with zero progress - "a few moments," not a real
  # roundtime/combat-scale wait. Confirmed in the field: a monster
  # wandering into the room while the script stood there repeating a
  # doomed move is exactly the failure mode this is meant to cut short.
  MOVE_STUCK_TIMEOUT_SECONDS = 10

  # group_sync: only actually publish to the shared Settings row this often
  # (unless something claim-worthy forces an immediate publish) - avoids
  # hammering the shared SQLite-backed blob with redundant writes once the
  # maze is mostly explored and little is changing tick to tick.
  SYNC_THROTTLE_SECONDS = 10
  # group_sync: how long a teammate's claim (mid-transport, mid-obstacle) is
  # trusted before being treated as stale - covers their process dying or
  # silently abandoning without ever publishing the clear.
  SYNC_CLAIM_TTL_SECONDS = 90
  # group_sync: cap on @recently_cleared_obstacles so it can't grow forever
  # over a long run.
  RECENTLY_CLEARED_CAP = 20
  # group_sync: how long merge_remote_pieces! refuses to re-adopt the exact
  # same descriptor+room a teammate's slice still claims :located, once this
  # character has personally just disproven it (see @rejected_locations
  # below) - long enough to outlast SYNC_THROTTLE_SECONDS so the teammate's
  # own next publish has a real chance to catch up.
  REJECTED_LOCATION_COOLDOWN_SECONDS = 30

  # Friendly NPC the guide spawns, floats through rooms with - never counts
  # as a hostile. Kept independent from inky.lic's own copy of this same
  # regex on purpose - this script never depends on Inky being loaded.
  FRIENDLY_NPC_REGEX = /floating spherical guide/i

  # Don't re-ask every single time the guide happens to be in whatever room
  # we're standing in (the guide room gets revisited constantly during
  # normal delivery) - but do re-ask often enough that a script restarted
  # mid-run (killed and relaunched after an error, say) catches up on
  # whatever was already announced before it died, the next time it
  # happens to pass the guide, rather than only ever learning about NEW
  # announcements from here on.
  GUIDE_STATUS_RECHECK_SECONDS = 60

  @in_run        = false
  @guide_room_id = nil
  @guide_room_confirmed = false # whether @guide_room_id is the real guide room, not just our entry point
  @last_guide_status_check_at = nil
  @run_started_at = nil
  @completions    = 0 # total successful run completions this session, for repeatevent reporting
  @last_room_id  = nil # last room we actually scanned - lets us notice the player moving us manually
  @rooms_moved_since_run_start = 0 # drives the every-3/every-10-rooms progress pings
  @surrender_triggered = false # surrendermania: set once we've surrendered, so maybe_end_run treats the run as over

  @needed         = {}   # descriptor => :needed/:located/:in_transit/:delivered/:claimed
  @seen           = {}   # descriptor => room_id (most recent sighting)
  @piece_location = {}   # descriptor => room_id (while :located)
  @transporting   = nil  # { descriptor:, } while actively pushing a piece
  @kick_arrival_uid = nil # one-shot grace flag - see continue_transport's "lost track" handling
  @delivered      = []
  @claimed_pieces = {}   # descriptor => room_id, informational only - see continue_transport

  # pacifist: descriptor => { room:, blocked_at: } - room it's currently
  # stuck in, kicked back there by "too dangerous" rather than fought
  # through, and when that last happened. Deprioritized by next_located_
  # descriptor in favor of anything not on this list, until either every
  # other :located piece is ALSO blocked (see @forced_piece) or
  # PACIFIST_BLOCKED_RETRY_SECONDS has passed since blocked_at, whichever
  # comes first.
  @blocked_pieces = {}
  # pacifist: the one descriptor next_located_descriptor has decided is
  # worth pushing through combat for, because every :located piece (this
  # one included) is blocked. continue_transport checks this to tell "the
  # one we're allowed to fight for" apart from "abandon and try elsewhere."
  @forced_piece = nil
  # pacifist: consecutive obstacle rooms process_obstacle_queue has skipped
  # in a row for having a hostile present, used the same way @forced_piece
  # is - once it's cycled through every logged obstacle without finding a
  # clear one, the next one gets cleared anyway rather than stalling.
  @obstacle_skip_streak = 0
  @last_resweep_at = nil # throttles resweep_for_missed_obstacles!
  @blocks_directive_active = false # set by ";inqui blocks" - see blocks_directive_tick
  @blocks_known_descriptors = [] # snapshot at ";inqui blocks" time - see handle_blocks

  # group_sync: shares discovered map/piece/obstacle state with teammates
  # also running InquiConundrum.lic, via a shared Settings row - see the
  # "multi-character cooperation" section below for the full mechanism.
  @last_sync_publish_at = nil # throttles sync_publish_local_state!
  @sync_dirty = false # set whenever local state changes something worth publishing
  @remote_claims = {} # descriptor/uid => { kind:, char:, room:, at: } - teammate in-progress work
  @remote_claims_by_char = {} # char_name => last claim key, so merge_remote_claim! can drop a stale one actively
  @piece_last_updated_at = {} # descriptor => Time.now.to_i, stamped wherever @piece_location is set
  @recently_cleared_obstacles = [] # rolling list of uids this character personally confirmed cleared
  # Tracked purely for awareness (shared via group_sync below) - bone-spike/
  # coral-tendril traps have no avoidance behavior of their own the way moss/
  # mushroom crawl-hazards do, so a teammate who's never personally seen a
  # given trap room has no way to know it's there at all otherwise. uid stays
  # in this list until handle_traps confirms the trap itself is actually
  # gone (destroyed by either character, or already gone on revisit) - see
  # handle_traps and path_avoiding_hazards below.
  @trap_rooms = []
  @recently_cleared_traps = [] # rolling list of uids this character personally confirmed trap-free
  @sync_scope_for_run = nil # frozen once per run at maybe_start_run time - never recomputed live
  @sync_force_pending = false # set by force_sync_publish! - consumed only from tick's own thread

  # Confirmed in the field: continue_transport demoting a descriptor back
  # to :needed because the piece genuinely isn't in this room anymore got
  # immediately undone by the very next sync_merge_remote_state! - a
  # teammate's still-stale published slice kept re-asserting the exact same
  # :located/uid we'd just personally disproven, which sent begin_transport/
  # continue_transport into a tight loop with no fput/move/pause anywhere
  # in it (the room never changes, so nothing ever yields) - 30,000+ log
  # lines in under a minute. @rejected_locations remembers "I just checked
  # this room and it wasn't there" per descriptor so merge_remote_pieces!
  # can refuse to re-adopt that exact same stale claim until the cooldown
  # passes (REJECTED_LOCATION_COOLDOWN_SECONDS above), without blocking a
  # genuinely different (new) remote location.
  @rejected_locations = {} # descriptor => { uid:, at: }

  @edges          = Hash.new { |h, k| h[k] = {} } # uid => { short_dir => dest_uid }
  @parent         = {}   # uid => { from:, back: } (back = short dir toward guide room)
  @exploration_cursor = nil # where the DFS was paused, so a piece detour back to the
                             # guide room doesn't get mistaken for the whole maze being done
  @fully_explored = false
  @all_known      = false
  @parsing_status = false # mid-way through reading an "ask guide about status" reply
  @idle_announced = false # whether we've already told the player we're fully caught up
  @last_location_report = nil # dedupes report_known_part_locations so it only reprints on change
  @last_status_update_at = nil # throttles the idle progress/time-left summary

  # What ;inqui status reports as the current operation. One of
  # :destroying_obstacle, :fetching, :transporting, :exploring, :idle.
  # @fetching_descriptor only applies while :fetching - @transporting
  # already carries its own descriptor once we're actually :transporting.
  @current_operation = :idle
  @fetching_descriptor = nil

  # True only across begin_transport's own navigate_to walk (the "fetching"
  # phase, before @transporting is set) - check_for_available_piece! must
  # not interrupt that walk just because the very piece it's walking toward
  # is the one that "became available." @transporting itself already
  # covers every other case where we're busy returning a piece.
  @suppress_piece_interrupt = false

  # DownstreamHook procs run on the socket-reading thread, not the script's
  # own thread, so Script.current (and therefore echo) doesn't resolve
  # there - it falls back to "(unknown script)". respond with an explicit
  # prefix instead, so messages are always clearly self-identified.
  # _respond (not respond) specifically - respond escapes '<'/'>' for mono
  # /profanity frontends, which would turn monsterbold_start/end's raw
  # <pushBold/>/<popBold/> tags into literal visible text instead of
  # formatting. _respond sends the string through unescaped.
  def self.say(message)
    _respond("#{monsterbold_start}[InquiConundrum: #{message}]#{monsterbold_end}")
  end

  def self.debug?
    !!setting(:debug)
  end

  # Plain, unformatted - debug output is diagnostic noise, never the
  # monsterbold treatment say() gives real player-facing messages.
  def self.debug_say(message)
    return unless debug?

    _respond("[InquiConundrum: DEBUG: #{message}]")
  end

  ## ---- persisted settings -----------------------------------------------
  #
  # Stored in UserVars (not local instance vars) so that ;inquiconundrum set
  # can change behavior while the long-running ;inquiconundrum loop is
  # already active - it just re-reads UserVars.inquiconundrum each time it
  # checks.

  def self.settings
    UserVars.inquiconundrum ||= {}
  end

  def self.setting(key)
    value = settings[key]
    value.nil? ? OPTION_DEFAULTS[key] : value
  end

  def self.destroy_traps?
    !!setting(:destroytraps)
  end

  def self.repeat_event?
    !!setting(:repeatevent)
  end

  def self.surrender_mania?
    !!setting(:surrendermania)
  end

  def self.pacifist?
    !!setting(:pacifist)
  end

  ## ---- startup diagnostics ------------------------------------------------
  #
  # A round-trip write+read against the actual Settings-backed SQLite db
  # (the same lich.db3/database_adapter.rb machinery group_sync depends on),
  # under its own dedicated scratch scope - never touches real run data, so
  # this is exempt from the group_sync section's "only the quartet may call
  # Settings.root_proxy_for/refresh_data" rule (that rule is about avoiding
  # lost-update races on the shared RUN state specifically; nothing else
  # ever reads or writes this scope, so there's no race to avoid here).
  #
  # Confirmed via database_adapter.rb: save_settings is a single upsert
  # statement, so a script killed and restarted mid-run can never leave a
  # half-written row behind in the db - worst case from restarting is
  # briefly-stale published state (already self-healing via the various
  # retry-window/TTL mechanisms elsewhere in this file), never corruption.
  # What this check actually guards against is the db file itself being
  # unreachable (permissions, disk, a stuck lock) - which would otherwise
  # only ever surface later as a silently-swallowed "group sync: ... failed"
  # debug line the first time something actually tried to use it.
  DB_HEALTH_CHECK_SCOPE = 'inquiconundrum_dbcheck'.freeze

  def self.check_database_health
    probe = Time.now.to_f
    Settings.refresh_data(DB_HEALTH_CHECK_SCOPE)
    shared = Settings.root_proxy_for(DB_HEALTH_CHECK_SCOPE)
    shared['probe'] = probe
    Settings.refresh_data(DB_HEALTH_CHECK_SCOPE)
    shared = Settings.root_proxy_for(DB_HEALTH_CHECK_SCOPE)

    if shared['probe'] == probe
      debug_say "database check: read/write round-trip OK"
      true
    else
      say "WARNING: database read/write check came back wrong (expected #{probe}, got #{shared['probe'].inspect}) - group sync with a teammate may not work correctly this session"
      false
    end
  rescue StandardError => e
    say "WARNING: database check failed (#{e.class}: #{e.message}) - group sync with a teammate may not work correctly this session"
    false
  end

  # group_sync gating - see the full "multi-character cooperation" section
  # below (after run lifecycle) for the rest of the mechanism and the
  # ground rules these helpers exist to support.

  # Group.members (not bare Group.nouns) so this triggers Group.maybe_check
  # if the roster has never been checked yet - Group.nouns reads the cached
  # roster directly and never checks on its own, which would otherwise make
  # this read as "no group" forever until something else happens to call
  # Group.check first.
  def self.group_sync_enabled?
    Group.members.map(&:noun).reject { |n| n == Char.name }.any?
  rescue StandardError
    false
  end

  def self.compute_sync_scope
    roster = ([Char.name] + Group.members.map(&:noun)).uniq.sort
    "inquiconundrum_group:#{roster.join(',')}"
  end

  # GameObj.npcs has no hostile/friendly distinction of its own - the guide
  # itself shows up there too and has to be filtered out by name.
  def self.hostile_present?
    GameObj.npcs.any? { |npc| npc.name !~ FRIENDLY_NPC_REGEX }
  end

  def self.show_settings
    settings_line = OPTION_KEYS.map { |key| "#{key}=#{setting(key)}" }.join(' | ')
    say "Current settings: #{settings_line}"
  end

  def self.handle_set(args)
    if args.empty?
      show_settings
      return
    end

    args.each do |pair|
      key_str, value_str = pair.split('=', 2)
      if key_str.nil? || value_str.nil?
        say "invalid option '#{pair}' - expected option=value"
        next
      end

      key = key_str.strip.downcase.to_sym
      unless OPTION_KEYS.include?(key)
        say "unknown option '#{key_str}' (valid: #{OPTION_KEYS.join(', ')})"
        next
      end

      value = value_str.strip =~ /^(?:true|yes|on|1)$/i ? true : false
      settings[key] = value
      say "set #{key} = #{value}"
    end
  end

  def self.strip_article(name)
    name.to_s.sub(/^(?:a|an|the)\s+/i, '').strip
  end

  def self.kick_phrase(descriptor)
    descriptor.split(' ').last(2).join(' ')
  end

  ## ---- message listener -------------------------------------------------

  # DownstreamHook procs run on the socket-reading thread, not this script's
  # own thread (same reasoning as say()'s _respond comment above) - fput
  # can't be called from there, so just queue it and let main_loop's
  # poll_background_events (on our own thread) do the actual surrendering.
  SURRENDER_QUEUE = Queue.new

  def self.install_listener
    DownstreamHook.add('inquiconundrum_listener', proc { |line|
      if (m = ANNOUNCE_REGEX.match(line))
        announce(strip_article(m[1]))
      end

      if (m = DELIVERY_REGEX.match(line))
        deliver(strip_article(m[1]))
      end

      if line =~ COMPLETE_REGEX && !@all_known
        @all_known = true
        say "guide has now announced all pieces needed (#{@needed.size})"
      end

      if line =~ SURRENDER_THRESHOLD_REGEX && surrender_mania?
        SURRENDER_QUEUE.push(true)
      end

      if line =~ STATUS_HEADER_REGEX
        @parsing_status = true
      elsif @parsing_status
        if line.strip.empty?
          # blank line inside the list - keep reading
        elsif (m = STATUS_ITEM_REGEX.match(line))
          announce(strip_article(m[1]))
        else
          @parsing_status = false
        end
      end

      line.scan(PIECE_DESCRIPTOR_REGEX).each do |(desc)|
        observe_descriptor(desc) if @needed.key?(desc.downcase)
      end

      if line =~ TIME_WARNING_REGEX
        say(line.gsub(/<[^>]+>/, '').strip)
      end

      line
    })
  end

  def self.remove_listener
    DownstreamHook.remove('inquiconundrum_listener')
  end

  ## ---- upstream command hook ---------------------------------------------
  #
  # ;send to <script> <msg> looks like the standard way to reach an
  # already-running script, but it doesn't actually work here: every
  # normal script (this one included) leaves Script#want_downstream at its
  # default of true, since that's what feeds get/get? their game text - so
  # ;send's payload lands in the same downstream_buffer as ordinary game
  # output, not unique_buffer, and just vanishes without ever matching one
  # of the regexes this script's DownstreamHook reads for. Killtracker.lic's
  # approach is the one that actually works: intercept ";inquiconundrum
  # .../;inqui ..." as the player types it, swallow it (return nil) so
  # Lich's own ";<script>" dispatch - and its "already running" rejection -
  # never even sees it, and queue whatever follows for main_loop to act on.
  CMD_QUEUE = Queue.new
  UPSTREAM_HOOK_ID = 'inquiconundrum_upstream'
  HOOK_CMD_RX = /^(?:<c>)?;(?:#{Regexp.escape(Script.current.name)}|inqui)(?:\s+(.*))?$/i

  def self.parse_upstream(command)
    if (m = HOOK_CMD_RX.match(command))
      CMD_QUEUE.push(m[1])
      nil
    else
      command
    end
  end

  def self.install_upstream_hook
    UpstreamHook.add(UPSTREAM_HOOK_ID, proc { |command| parse_upstream(command) })
  end

  def self.remove_upstream_hook
    UpstreamHook.remove(UPSTREAM_HOOK_ID)
  end

  def self.drain_cmd_queue
    handle_command(CMD_QUEUE.pop) until CMD_QUEUE.empty?
  end

  # Drains SURRENDER_QUEUE (see install_listener) and actually sends the two
  # surrenders here, on our own thread - fput can't be called from the
  # DownstreamHook proc that detected the threshold message. Surrendering
  # ends the run immediately regardless of room/timeout, same as winning -
  # @surrender_triggered short-circuits maybe_end_run's usual conditions.
  def self.check_surrender_threshold
    triggered = false
    until SURRENDER_QUEUE.empty?
      SURRENDER_QUEUE.pop
      triggered = true
    end
    return unless triggered

    say "surrendermania: passed the prize threshold - surrendering to end the match"
    # Confirmed in the field: a flat pause(1) between the two surrenders
    # wasn't long enough to clear whatever roundtime the first one left
    # behind - the second fput went out while still in RT and the game
    # silently dropped it, never actually completing the surrender. We
    # still set @surrender_triggered below regardless of whether the game
    # actually accepted it, which is exactly what let this go unnoticed:
    # the script believed the run was over and started wrapping up
    # (stow/gird/walk back) while still physically standing in the still-
    # active event, instead of waiting for the real ejection.
    wait_out_roundtime
    send_command('surrender')
    wait_out_roundtime
    send_command('surrender')
    @surrender_triggered = true
  end

  # main_loop only drains CMD_QUEUE/SURRENDER_QUEUE between ticks, but a
  # single tick can stay busy for a long time (a multi-hit obstacle, a long
  # kick/move retry, a deep exploration recursion) without ever returning
  # control back up to main_loop - confirmed in the field: ;inqui
  # status/help/set typed mid-obstacle-kill just sat queued, looking exactly
  # like the script was ignoring them. Called from inside the tight polling
  # loops below (wait_for_destroy_outcome, wait_for_kick_outcome,
  # wait_for_room_arrival, move's retry gap) so both upstream commands and
  # the surrender threshold get handled within their ~0.05-0.1s poll
  # interval instead of waiting for the whole tick to finish.
  def self.poll_background_events
    drain_cmd_queue
    check_surrender_threshold
  end

  # Confirmed in the field: a piece becoming :located mid-exploration (the
  # guide announces it, and we'd already seen it somewhere) didn't get
  # acted on until continue_exploration's current recursive dig (explore_
  # exit/explore_new_exits can chain through many rooms before naturally
  # returning) finished on its own - looked like aimless wandering right
  # past a piece we already knew the location of. Raises PieceBecameAvailable
  # to unwind straight back to tick's rescue instead of waiting for that.
  # Silent no-op while actively transporting (@transporting) or mid-fetch-
  # walk for a piece (@suppress_piece_interrupt) - in both cases we're
  # already doing exactly this, just not finished yet.
  #
  # A piece next_located_descriptor hands back that's ever been pacifist-
  # blocked (still within its retry window via the @forced_piece fallback,
  # or past it and just due for a recheck) only interrupts whatever's
  # currently in progress (exploring, destroying an obstacle) if it's
  # actually closer to the guide than wherever we currently are - a fresh,
  # never-blocked piece still always interrupts unconditionally, same as
  # ever. Finishing something already closer (or equally close) makes more
  # sense than detouring for a recheck that doesn't even save a trip.
  def self.check_for_available_piece!
    return if @transporting || @suppress_piece_interrupt

    descriptor = next_located_descriptor
    return unless descriptor

    if @blocked_pieces.key?(descriptor)
      # Same reasoning as maybe_abandon_for_closer_piece: distance-to-guide
      # alone says nothing about how far this piece's room actually is
      # from wherever we currently stand - only interrupt if it's a
      # genuinely short detour from here, not just "closer to the guide"
      # in tree terms while sitting at the far end of an unrelated branch.
      travel = tree_distance(XMLData.room_id, @piece_location[descriptor])
      return if travel.nil?

      return unless travel + distance_to_guide(@piece_location[descriptor]) < distance_to_guide(XMLData.room_id)
    end

    raise PieceBecameAvailable
  end

  # Mirrors maybe_end_run's own condition exactly, just without the side
  # effects - maybe_end_run still does the actual ending (printing,
  # @in_run, requeue_for_next_run) the next time tick's top runs it. This
  # only needs to fire the instant ending becomes true, from wherever in
  # tick's call tree we happen to be, so a stuck or misled move/explore
  # loop can never block it.
  def self.check_for_run_end!
    return unless @in_run
    ended_by_room = !!(XMLData.room_title =~ END_ROOM_REGEX)
    raise RunEnding if ended_by_room || @surrender_triggered || (Time.now - @run_started_at) > MAX_RUN_SECONDS
  end

  # Same as poll_background_events, but also raises via
  # check_for_available_piece!/check_for_run_end!. Only safe to call from inside tick's own
  # call tree (continue_exploration, destroy_obstacle, begin_transport's
  # navigate_to, continue_transport), which tick wraps in a rescue for
  # exactly this. Confirmed in the field: main_loop's own top-level poll
  # used to call this same combined check directly, BEFORE tick (and its
  # rescue) ever runs - that raise had nowhere to go but main_loop's
  # generic StandardError handler, which just logged it and retried
  # forever without resolving anything, since nothing about the underlying
  # condition (a piece sitting there :located) ever changes between
  # retries. main_loop now calls the plain, non-raising poll_background_
  # events instead; only the loops below (already inside tick's rescue)
  # use this one.
  def self.poll_background_events!
    poll_background_events
    check_for_run_end!
    check_for_available_piece!
  end

  # The global wait_out_roundtime sleeps out the whole remaining roundtime in one
  # uninterrupted call, with no chance to drain CMD_QUEUE/SURRENDER_QUEUE in
  # between - confirmed in the field: ;inqui status/help typed during
  # roundtime just sat there until the roundtime actually cleared, even
  # though every poll loop elsewhere in this script was already fixed to
  # answer immediately. checkrt (the same remaining-seconds value wait_out_roundtime
  # itself reads) sliced into short waits instead, draining background
  # events between each one.
  def self.wait_out_roundtime
    loop do
      remaining = checkrt
      break if remaining <= 0

      poll_background_events!
      sleep [remaining, 0.1].min
    end
  end

  def self.announce(descriptor)
    descriptor = descriptor.downcase
    return if @needed.key?(descriptor)

    @needed[descriptor] = :needed
    @idle_announced = false
    say "guide needs a #{descriptor}"

    if @seen.key?(descriptor)
      say "We know where this is, Let's go get it!"
      debug_say "#{descriptor} already in memory (room #{@seen[descriptor]}) - will head there"
    else
      debug_say "#{descriptor} not yet seen - continuing to log rooms until it's found"
    end

    observe_descriptor(descriptor)
  end

  def self.deliver(descriptor)
    descriptor = descriptor.downcase
    return unless @needed.key?(descriptor)
    return if @needed[descriptor] == :delivered # already counted - see continue_transport

    @needed[descriptor] = :delivered
    @delivered << descriptor
    @transporting = nil if @transporting && @transporting[:descriptor] == descriptor
    say "delivered #{descriptor} (#{@delivered.size}/#{@needed.size} known so far)"

    # Confirmed in the field: this was the one major state transition in
    # the whole file that never marked @sync_dirty or force-published -
    # located/transport-started/obstacle-claimed-or-cleared all do. Without
    # this, a delivery only ever reached a teammate as a side effect of
    # something UNRELATED dirtying state afterward (a new edge, a newly
    # seen piece) - if nothing else happened to do that, the other
    # character genuinely never learned this piece was already done for
    # the rest of the run, and could go on to needlessly re-fetch/re-claim
    # it.
    @sync_dirty = true
    force_sync_publish!
  end

  def self.observe_descriptor(descriptor)
    return unless @seen.key?(descriptor) && @needed[descriptor] == :needed

    @needed[descriptor] = :located
    @piece_location[descriptor] = @seen[descriptor]
    @piece_last_updated_at[descriptor] = Time.now.to_i
    @sync_dirty = true
    force_sync_publish!
  end

  ## ---- room scanning -----------------------------------------------------

  # The "You also see ..." list (parts, traps, vines, moss formations) is
  # the 'room objs' component, which Lich parses into GameObj.loot (and
  # GameObj.npcs for anything bolded) - NOT GameObj.room_desc. room_desc
  # only holds things embedded directly in the prose paragraph itself.
  def self.scan_room(uid)
    added = 0

    GameObj.loot.each do |obj|
      next if obj.name.nil?

      if (m = PIECE_DESCRIPTOR_REGEX.match(strip_article(obj.name)))
        descriptor = m[1].downcase

        unless @seen.key?(descriptor)
          added += 1
          debug_say "new part seen: #{descriptor} (room #{uid})"
        end

        @seen[descriptor] = uid
        if @needed[descriptor] == :needed
          @needed[descriptor] = :located
          @piece_location[descriptor] = uid
          @piece_last_updated_at[descriptor] = Time.now.to_i
          @sync_dirty = true
          debug_say "#{descriptor} matches a needed piece - marking located"
          force_sync_publish!
        end
      end
    end

    say "added #{added} part#{'s' unless added == 1} to memory, total = #{@seen.size}"
  end

  # Both vines ("covering the passage X") and thornbound wards ("blocking
  # the passage X") seal off a specific exit and are missing from
  # checkpaths/short_exits entirely - the room description names the
  # direction, but "Obvious paths" just won't list it.
  def self.directional_obstacles(regex, direction_regex)
    obstacles = {}
    GameObj.loot.each do |obj|
      next unless obj.name =~ regex

      dir = obj.name[direction_regex, 1]
      next unless dir

      # SHORTDIR's keys are all lowercase - direction_regex is case
      # insensitive, so without downcasing here, a capture with different
      # casing silently looks up to nil. That nil then gets used as a real
      # hash key/direction by every caller (candidate_exits, move, ...),
      # which sends a blank command forever instead of ever moving - the
      # script just sits there retrying "move  didn't go anywhere".
      short = SHORTDIR[dir.downcase]
      obstacles[short] = obj if short
    end
    obstacles
  end

  def self.current_vines
    directional_obstacles(VINE_REGEX, VINE_DIRECTION_REGEX)
  end

  # Not every vine's text matches VINE_DIRECTION_REGEX, so current_vines
  # alone misses some - those still seal off an exit (and silently hide
  # any part behind it from exploration) even though we can't tell which
  # direction from the wording. Used by handle_obstacles_on_entry to make
  # sure every vine we can attack gets destroyed, named direction or not.
  def self.all_vines
    GameObj.loot.select { |obj| obj.name =~ VINE_REGEX }
  end

  def self.current_wards
    directional_obstacles(WARD_REGEX, WARD_DIRECTION_REGEX)
  end

  # Same deal as all_vines - confirmed in the field that at least one
  # obstacle variant phrases its direction as "blocking the path X"
  # instead of "blocking the passage X" (a vine-tangled wall did this),
  # so wards can't be assumed to always match WARD_DIRECTION_REGEX either.
  # Used by handle_obstacles_on_entry so a ward we can't parse a direction
  # from still gets killed instead of permanently sealing off whatever's
  # behind it.
  def self.all_wards
    GameObj.loot.select { |obj| obj.name =~ WARD_REGEX }
  end

  def self.current_traps
    GameObj.loot.select { |obj| obj.name =~ TRAP_REGEX }
  end

  # Ground hazards that aren't worth fighting through - kneel and crawl
  # past them instead of risking a trigger by walking normally.
  def self.crawl_hazard_in_room?
    XMLData.room_description =~ MOSS_REGEX ||
      XMLData.room_description =~ MUSHROOM_REGEX ||
      GameObj.loot.any? { |o| o.name =~ MOSS_REGEX || o.name =~ MUSHROOM_REGEX }
  end

  ## ---- hazards ------------------------------------------------------------

  # The kill's *first* response line is always "You attack ..." flavor
  # text - the real outcome (destroyed, gird needed, or already gone)
  # only arrives after that, possibly after the roundtime.
  GIRD_NEEDED_REGEX     = /You'd probably have more luck with an appropriate weapon/i
  DESTROY_SUCCESS_REGEX = /You have destroyed/i
  DESTROY_GONE_REGEX    = /What were you referring to/i

  # Polls (without ever resending the kill command) until the real outcome
  # line shows up. wait_out_roundtime already absorbed the roundtime itself - an
  # obstacle that's actually dead announces it within a line or two of
  # that, so this only needs to cover server lag, not the swing that
  # didn't finish it off. Confirmed in the field: a 20-second value here
  # meant every single multi-hit obstacle (which never produces an outcome
  # line for a swing that doesn't finish it) sat idle for a full 20 seconds
  # per attempt before retrying, even though nothing was ever going to
  # arrive - 3x that with the retry loop below. Even the 3-second value
  # this was first dropped to (1.20.0) still added a flat 3 seconds of dead
  # waiting on top of every single roundtime for that same common case
  # (10 sec RT measured as 13-14 sec end to end). A short timeout costs
  # nothing when the real text does arrive late (a noisy room can still
  # delay it past this window) - it just means one extra harmless "kill"
  # that the game answers with "What were you referring to?" (:gone),
  # which resolves the obstacle anyway.
  def self.wait_for_destroy_outcome(timeout = 1)
    deadline = Time.now + timeout
    next_yield_at = Time.now + 0.1
    loop do
      line = get?
      if line
        return :gird_needed if line =~ GIRD_NEEDED_REGEX
        return :destroyed   if line =~ DESTROY_SUCCESS_REGEX
        return :gone        if line =~ DESTROY_GONE_REGEX
      end
      return nil if Time.now > deadline

      # A non-matching line must not loop straight back to the top with no
      # sleep/poll at all - heavy unrelated combat text could keep this
      # spinning with zero yield points for the entire timeout, freezing
      # this script silently and delaying Script.kill until something
      # finally gave it a checkpoint. But sleeping on *every* line is its
      # own bug - confirmed in the field: it turned a room's whole burst of
      # already-buffered description lines (title, paragraph, objects,
      # exits) into one sleep apiece, adding the better part of a second
      # to every single room move for no reason, since none of that was
      # ever waiting on anything. Only actually sleep once per ~0.1s of
      # wall-clock time - an empty buffer (nothing left to drain right
      # now) always qualifies; a non-empty one only forces it past that
      # cap, so a fast-arriving burst still drains at full speed.
      next if line && Time.now < next_yield_at

      poll_background_events!
      sleep 0.1
      next_yield_at = Time.now + 0.1
    end
  end

  # GameObj.loot doesn't necessarily drop a destroyed object the instant
  # it dies - the room's loot list only refreshes on its own schedule - so
  # looping on "is obj still in GameObj.loot" can keep re-issuing "kill
  # #id" against something already dead, which the game answers with
  # "What were you referring to?" forever. Trust the game's own outcome
  # text instead of GameObj.loot's staleness.
  # Returns whether obj actually ended up destroyed/gone - process_obstacle_
  # queue needs to know this, not just assume every kill worked, before
  # treating the direction it was blocking as safe to walk into.
  def self.destroy_obstacle(obj)
    @current_operation = :destroying_obstacle
    attempts = 0
    loop do
      wait_while_paused_externally
      send_command("kill ##{obj.id}")
      wait_out_roundtime
      outcome = wait_for_destroy_outcome

      case outcome
      when :gird_needed
        send_command('gird')
        wait_out_roundtime
      when :destroyed, :gone
        return true
      else
        # An unclear (timed-out) outcome almost always just means this
        # swing didn't finish the obstacle off, so no outcome line was ever
        # coming - swing again right away. attempt_move's own retry-forever
        # loop is the backstop for an obstacle that genuinely never
        # resolves after several attempts here.
        attempts += 1
        if attempts >= 3
          debug_say "kill ##{obj.id} outcome unclear (#{outcome.inspect}) after #{attempts} attempts - giving up on this obstacle"
          return false
        end
        debug_say "kill ##{obj.id} outcome unclear (#{outcome.inspect}) - retrying (attempt #{attempts})"
      end
    end
  end

  # Logs/clears @trap_rooms for awareness regardless of destroytraps - a
  # teammate who's never personally stood in this exact room otherwise has
  # no way to know a trap is here at all, since (unlike moss/mushroom)
  # nothing about a bone-spike/coral-tendril trap is visible from "Obvious
  # paths" or any other ambient state. Only actually attacks it (and clears
  # the log entry once confirmed gone) when destroytraps is on.
  def self.handle_traps
    uid = XMLData.room_id
    traps = current_traps

    if traps.empty?
      if @trap_rooms.delete(uid)
        @recently_cleared_traps = (@recently_cleared_traps + [uid]).last(RECENTLY_CLEARED_CAP)
        @sync_dirty = true
        debug_say "room #{uid}'s trap is gone (destroyed earlier, by us or a teammate) - no longer a hazard"
      end
      return
    end

    unless @trap_rooms.include?(uid)
      @trap_rooms << uid
      @sync_dirty = true
      debug_say "room #{uid} has #{traps.size} trap(s) - logged for awareness"
    end

    return unless destroy_traps?

    if traps.all? { |trap| destroy_obstacle(trap) }
      @trap_rooms.delete(uid)
      @recently_cleared_traps = (@recently_cleared_traps + [uid]).last(RECENTLY_CLEARED_CAP)
      @sync_dirty = true
      debug_say "room #{uid}'s trap(s) destroyed - no longer a hazard"
    end
  end

  # Vines/wards are never destroyed on first sight anymore - logged for
  # later instead. Destroying one is comparatively slow (a multi-hit kill
  # plus roundtime, every time), and most needed pieces turn out to sit
  # behind freely-walkable exits - fighting through every obstacle the
  # instant the DFS first bumps into it meant slow combat was constantly
  # interleaved with movement before we'd even confirmed it was necessary.
  # Just records the room here; process_obstacle_queue works through the
  # backlog once every freely-reachable room has actually been visited
  # (see continue_exploration's @phase switch).
  #
  # Uses all_vines/all_wards (not current_vines/current_wards) specifically
  # so an obstacle we can't parse a direction from still gets logged -
  # otherwise checkpaths just never lists the exit it's sealing and it'd be
  # invisible to this check entirely.
  def self.handle_obstacles_on_entry
    obstacles = all_vines + all_wards
    return if obstacles.empty?

    uid = XMLData.room_id
    return if @obstacle_rooms.include?(uid)

    @obstacle_rooms << uid
    @sync_dirty = true
    debug_say "room #{uid} has #{obstacles.size} obstacle(s) - logged for later clearing"
  end

  ## ---- combat ---------------------------------------------------------
  #
  # Monsters never get fought during plain exploration - they don't attack
  # and can't be attacked at that point anyway. The ONLY time combat is
  # ever this script's problem is when a kick is rejected as "too
  # dangerous" while actively pushing a found piece home. That's the one
  # and only place this gets called. Pause is literal (pause_script) and
  # waits for the player to clear it rather than guessing at attack
  # commands or assuming a particular combat script. pause_script only
  # sets the paused flag - it doesn't block by itself - so explicitly
  # sleep until the player runs ;unpause inquiconundrum.
  def self.wait_for_player_to_clear_room(reason = "something here is blocking the way")
    say "PAUSED: #{reason} - kill it, then ;unpause inquiconundrum to continue"
    debug_say "pausing in room #{XMLData.room_id} (#{XMLData.room_title.to_s.strip}); npcs here: #{GameObj.npcs.map(&:name).join(', ')}"
    pause_script
    sleep 0.2 while Script.current.paused?
    debug_say "unpaused, resuming"
  end

  # Script.pause/Script.unpause just flip a flag on the target script - they
  # don't block anything by themselves (see the comment on
  # wait_for_player_to_clear_room above). That's normally fine since this
  # script only ever pauses itself. But it also means an outside script
  # (e.g. inky.lic, clearing a hostile out of the way with bigshot while we'd
  # otherwise blindly keep "kill"-ing an obstacle through it) can
  # Script.pause('inquiconundrum') and have nothing actually happen unless we
  # check for it ourselves. destroy_obstacle's retry loop calls this between
  # every attempt for exactly that reason.
  def self.wait_while_paused_externally
    return unless Script.current.paused?

    debug_say "paused externally - waiting to resume"
    sleep 0.2 while Script.current.paused?
    debug_say "resumed"
  end

  ## ---- low-level game I/O ---------------------------------------------------
  #
  # Confirmed in the field: the game itself can hang/crash mid-session
  # (server stops responding entirely, TCP connection still nominally open)
  # without ever actually closing the socket for a while - fput's own
  # 60s-no-response timeout already detects and echoes that for a single
  # command, but every call site here used bare fput directly, so the
  # script just silently tried the NEXT command, got ANOTHER full 60s of
  # silence, then the next, forever - each cycle a full minute of nothing
  # visible at all. Looked exactly like "the script went unresponsive" even
  # though technically it kept retrying the whole time. send_command wraps
  # every fput call site in this script (mechanical replacement, see
  # below) so CONNECTION_UNRESPONSIVE_THRESHOLD consecutive timeouts - a
  # much stronger signal than just one slow response - pauses the script
  # and says so loudly instead of quietly grinding through 60s cycles
  # forever. The player can still type ;unpause (or anything else) through
  # Lich's local connection even while the upstream game connection itself
  # is the thing that's actually dead, exactly as already happened in the
  # field before this existed (manual ";kill inqui" was the only way out).
  @consecutive_fput_timeouts = 0
  CONNECTION_UNRESPONSIVE_THRESHOLD = 2

  def self.send_command(message, *args)
    result = fput(message, *args)

    if result == false
      @consecutive_fput_timeouts += 1
      if @consecutive_fput_timeouts >= CONNECTION_UNRESPONSIVE_THRESHOLD
        say "PAUSED: no response from the game for #{@consecutive_fput_timeouts} commands in a row - the game may have crashed or your connection may be down. Check it, then ;unpause inquiconundrum to continue"
        pause_script
        sleep 0.2 while Script.current.paused?
        say "unpaused, resuming"
        @consecutive_fput_timeouts = 0
      end
    else
      @consecutive_fput_timeouts = 0
    end

    result
  end

  ## ---- movement -----------------------------------------------------------

  # Always the last thing to arrive in a room description, so waiting for
  # it (instead of returning on whatever line happens to come back first)
  # guarantees the room's full object list - including any parts - has
  # already been parsed into GameObj.loot before we go look at it.
  ROOM_ARRIVED_REGEX = /Obvious (?:paths|exits)|You notice no obvious exits from here\.?/i

  # fput's own waitingfor mechanism re-sends the command whenever a line
  # doesn't match - exactly wrong here, since a room description is
  # several lines and re-sending "north" partway through it would move us
  # again. So send the command exactly once (plain fput, first-line
  # return) and separately drain (without ever resending anything) until
  # the arrival marker shows up or we give up waiting.
  def self.fput_move(command)
    send_command(command)
    wait_for_room_arrival
  end

  def self.wait_for_room_arrival(timeout = 2)
    deadline = Time.now + timeout
    next_yield_at = Time.now + 0.05
    loop do
      line = get?
      return if line && line =~ ROOM_ARRIVED_REGEX
      return if Time.now > deadline

      # Same fix as wait_for_destroy_outcome/wait_for_kick_outcome - a
      # non-matching line must not loop straight back to the top with no
      # sleep/poll at all (heavy unrelated text could spin this with zero
      # yield points for the whole timeout), but sleeping on *every* line
      # is its own bug - confirmed in the field: this is called on every
      # single room move, and a room's whole burst of already-buffered
      # description lines (title, paragraph, objects, exits) turned into
      # one sleep apiece, adding the better part of a second to every move
      # for no reason. Only actually sleep once per ~0.05s of wall-clock
      # time - a fast-arriving burst still drains at full speed.
      next if line && Time.now < next_yield_at

      poll_background_events!
      sleep 0.05
      next_yield_at = Time.now + 0.05
    end
  end

  # Single attempt at moving; returns whether the room actually changed.
  # Never pauses for traps or monsters here - see wait_for_player_to_clear_room
  # for the one legitimate place combat can block this script.
  def self.attempt_move(direction)
    starting_room = XMLData.room_id

    # Traps (the mushroom trap knockdown, moss fall, etc.) can leave us
    # prone/sitting/kneeling outside of our own deliberate kneel-and-crawl
    # handling below. That's always auto-recoverable - just stand up.
    if checknotstanding
      debug_say "not standing - standing up before moving #{direction}"
      send_command('stand')
      wait_out_roundtime
    end

    obstacle = current_vines[direction] || current_wards[direction]
    if obstacle
      # Always destroyed, no matter what - it might be sealing off a room
      # with a needed part in it.
      destroy_obstacle(obstacle)
      fput_move(direction)
      wait_out_roundtime
    elsif crawl_hazard_in_room?
      send_command('kneel')
      wait_out_roundtime
      fput_move("crawl #{direction}")
      wait_out_roundtime
      send_command('stand')
      wait_out_roundtime
    else
      fput_move(direction)
      wait_out_roundtime
    end

    XMLData.room_id != starting_room
  end

  # Moves in a direction, retrying quietly (no pausing - traps and the
  # like are never worth bothering the player over) until it actually
  # succeeds. Callers can always assume the room changed by the time this
  # returns.
  def self.move(direction)
    # A nil/blank direction (e.g. a bad SHORTDIR lookup somewhere upstream)
    # would otherwise retry forever sending a blank command and never
    # actually move - fail loudly instead of silently spamming the game.
    raise "move called with a blank direction" if direction.to_s.empty?

    attempts = 0
    stuck_since = Time.now
    until attempt_move(direction)
      attempts += 1

      if Time.now - stuck_since > MOVE_STUCK_TIMEOUT_SECONDS
        raise StuckMove.new(
          "move #{direction} from room #{XMLData.room_id} went nowhere after #{attempts} attempts over #{MOVE_STUCK_TIMEOUT_SECONDS}s",
          uid: XMLData.room_id, direction: direction
        )
      end

      debug_say "move #{direction} didn't go anywhere (attempt #{attempts}), retrying"
      poll_background_events!
      pause 1
    end
  end

  def self.record_edge(from_uid, direction, to_uid)
    @edges[from_uid][direction] = to_uid
    @edges[to_uid][reverse_direction(direction)] = from_uid
    @sync_dirty = true
  end

  def self.find_direction(from_uid, to_uid)
    @edges[from_uid].find { |_dir, dest| dest == to_uid }&.first
  end

  # We may start exploring before ever finding the guide's actual room, so
  # the navigation tree gets provisionally rooted wherever we happen to
  # start. Once the real guide room turns up, re-anchor the tree there by
  # reversing parentage along the chain from the old root to it - every
  # other branch of the tree is untouched.
  def self.reroot_tree(new_root)
    return if new_root == @guide_room_id || @parent[new_root].nil?

    chain = []
    node = new_root
    while node
      chain.unshift(node)
      break if node == @guide_room_id

      node = @parent[node] && @parent[node][:from]
    end

    (chain.length - 1).downto(1) do |i|
      child = chain[i - 1]
      parent_node = chain[i]
      @parent[child] = { from: parent_node, back: find_direction(child, parent_node) }
    end

    @parent[new_root] = { from: nil, back: nil }
  end

  def self.short_exits
    paths = checkpaths
    paths ? paths.compact : []
  end

  ## ---- room entry handling -------------------------------------------------

  def self.on_room_entered(uid)
    @last_room_id = uid
    @rooms_moved_since_run_start += 1
    report_room_progress

    if !@guide_room_confirmed && XMLData.room_title =~ START_ROOM_REGEX
      debug_say "confirmed the guide's room is #{uid}"
      reroot_tree(uid) if uid != @guide_room_id
      @guide_room_id = uid
      @guide_room_confirmed = true
    end

    maybe_ask_guide_for_status

    scan_room(uid)
    handle_traps
    handle_obstacles_on_entry
  end

  # Whenever the guide is physically standing in whatever room we just
  # entered - not just the one special-cased first sighting of the guide's
  # own room - ask it for status, throttled to GUIDE_STATUS_RECHECK_SECONDS.
  # The reply gets parsed by the listener (STATUS_HEADER_REGEX/STATUS_ITEM_
  # REGEX) into ordinary announce() calls, which are already idempotent
  # against anything we already know about - so this is always safe to
  # call, and is exactly what lets a script that got killed and restarted
  # mid-run (an error, say) catch back up on whatever the guide had already
  # announced before it died, the next time it happens to cross paths with
  # the guide, rather than only ever learning about announcements made
  # AFTER the restart.
  def self.maybe_ask_guide_for_status
    return unless GameObj.npcs.any? { |npc| npc.name =~ FRIENDLY_NPC_REGEX }
    return if @last_guide_status_check_at && (Time.now - @last_guide_status_check_at) < GUIDE_STATUS_RECHECK_SECONDS

    @last_guide_status_check_at = Time.now
    debug_say "spirit guide is here - asking for status to catch up on anything already announced"
    send_command('ask guide about status')
  end

  ## ---- piece transport --------------------------------------------------

  # The kick's *first* response line is always "you prepare to shove it...
  # gathering your strength" flavor text - the real outcome only arrives
  # after the roundtime, as one of these.
  KICK_DANGER_REGEX  = /too dangerous/i
  KICK_FAILED_REGEX  = /won't budge|can't kick|don't see|nothing happens/i
  KICK_SUCCESS_REGEX = /pushing it into the (?:next|adjoining) room/i

  # Polls (without ever resending the kick command - that would just
  # shove it again) until the real post-roundtime outcome line shows up.
  def self.wait_for_kick_outcome(timeout = 20)
    deadline = Time.now + timeout
    next_yield_at = Time.now + 0.1
    loop do
      line = get?
      if line
        return :danger  if line =~ KICK_DANGER_REGEX
        return :failed  if line =~ KICK_FAILED_REGEX
        return :success if line =~ KICK_SUCCESS_REGEX
      end
      return nil if Time.now > deadline

      # A non-matching line must not loop straight back to the top with no
      # sleep/poll at all - this has the longest timeout of the three
      # (20s), so heavy unrelated combat text (bigshot actively fighting
      # whatever made the kick "too dangerous" in the first place) could
      # keep this spinning with zero yield points for the whole window,
      # freezing this script silently and delaying Script.kill until the
      # text let up. But sleeping on *every* line is its own bug -
      # confirmed in the field: it added the better part of a second to
      # every single room move elsewhere (see wait_for_room_arrival). Only
      # actually sleep once per ~0.1s of wall-clock time - a fast-arriving
      # burst still drains at full speed.
      next if line && Time.now < next_yield_at

      poll_background_events!
      sleep 0.1
      next_yield_at = Time.now + 0.1
    end
  end

  def self.begin_transport(descriptor)
    target_uid = @piece_location[descriptor]
    @current_operation = :fetching
    @fetching_descriptor = descriptor
    @suppress_piece_interrupt = true
    debug_say "heading from room #{XMLData.room_id} to room #{target_uid} to fetch #{descriptor}"
    begin
      navigate_to(target_uid)
    ensure
      # Must clear even if navigate_to raises (e.g. explore_new_exits'
      # "expected to be in room X" guard) - otherwise check_for_available_
      # piece! would stay permanently suppressed for the rest of the run.
      @suppress_piece_interrupt = false
    end
    @needed[descriptor] = :in_transit
    @transporting = { descriptor: descriptor }
    @current_operation = :transporting
    @sync_dirty = true
    force_sync_publish! # teammates should see this claim ASAP, not wait out the throttle
    say "picked up trail of #{descriptor}, pushing it home"
  end

  # Only even tries the BFS route when a trap is actually known about -
  # for the common case (no traps logged yet), behavior is byte-for-byte
  # the old tree-walk, zero added risk. Once a trap room IS known, prefers
  # a path that avoids it (this maze's confirmed cycles sometimes really do
  # offer another way around) and only falls through to the tree-walk if
  # the avoiding search can't find any route at all (e.g. @edges doesn't
  # yet have full connectivity to target_uid).
  def self.navigate_to(target_uid)
    return if XMLData.room_id == target_uid

    if @trap_rooms.any?
      avoiding = path_avoiding_traps(XMLData.room_id, target_uid)
      if avoiding
        avoiding.each { |dir| move(dir); on_room_entered(XMLData.room_id) }
        return
      end
    end

    path = path_from_root(target_uid)
    walk_to_root
    path.each { |dir| move(dir); on_room_entered(XMLData.room_id) }
  end

  # General shortest-path search over the full known @edges graph (not just
  # the @parent breadcrumb tree, which only ever has ONE path between any
  # two rooms) - optionally treating avoid's rooms as impassable so a
  # detour can be found around them when this maze's cycles actually offer
  # one. Returns a list of directions, or nil if to_uid isn't reachable
  # from from_uid via @edges at all (callers fall back to the tree-based
  # path in that case, same as ever).
  def self.bfs_path(from_uid, to_uid, avoid: [])
    return [] if from_uid == to_uid

    visited = { from_uid => true }
    queue = [[from_uid, []]]
    until queue.empty?
      current, path = queue.shift
      @edges[current].each do |dir, neighbor|
        next if visited[neighbor]
        next if avoid.include?(neighbor) && neighbor != to_uid

        new_path = path + [dir]
        return new_path if neighbor == to_uid

        visited[neighbor] = true
        queue << [neighbor, new_path]
      end
    end
    nil
  end

  # Prefers a path that avoids every known @trap_rooms entry; falls back to
  # allowing them through if no avoiding route exists at all - a known
  # trap is still strictly better to walk past than to never reach the
  # target over, and nil (not an empty/wrong path) only when to_uid isn't
  # reachable via @edges yet either way.
  def self.path_avoiding_traps(from_uid, to_uid)
    bfs_path(from_uid, to_uid, avoid: @trap_rooms) || bfs_path(from_uid, to_uid)
  end

  def self.walk_to_root
    until XMLData.room_id == @guide_room_id
      back = @parent[XMLData.room_id] && @parent[XMLData.room_id][:back]
      break unless back

      move(back)
    end
  end

  def self.path_from_root(uid)
    path = []
    node = uid
    while node && node != @guide_room_id
      info = @parent[node]
      break unless info

      parent_uid = info[:from]
      forward_dir = @edges[parent_uid].find { |_dir, dest| dest == node }&.first
      path.unshift(forward_dir)
      node = parent_uid
    end
    path.compact
  end

  # Same as rooms_remaining_to_guide, but Float::INFINITY instead of nil for
  # an unreachable room - lets every distance comparison (min_by, <, etc.)
  # just work without a separate nil check at every call site.
  def self.distance_to_guide(uid)
    rooms_remaining_to_guide(uid) || Float::INFINITY
  end

  # "Always err to return parts closest to the guide" - used everywhere a
  # piece gets chosen among multiple located candidates (next_located_
  # descriptor's normal pick, pacifist's unblocked/retry-eligible pick, and
  # maybe_abandon_for_closer_piece's mid-transport comparison) so all of
  # them agree on the same priority instead of drifting independently.
  def self.closest_by_distance(descriptors)
    descriptors.min_by { |d| distance_to_guide(@piece_location[d]) }
  end

  # Counts moves from uid back to the guide room along the same @parent
  # breadcrumb trail walk_to_root/path_from_root walk - nil if uid isn't
  # connected to the known map at all (no path to count).
  def self.rooms_remaining_to_guide(uid)
    steps = 0
    node = uid
    while node != @guide_room_id
      info = @parent[node]
      return nil unless info && info[:from]

      node = info[:from]
      steps += 1
    end
    steps
  end

  # uid's full ancestor chain (itself, its @parent, its parent's parent,
  # ...) up to the guide room - used by tree_distance below to find the
  # lowest common ancestor of two rooms.
  def self.ancestor_chain(uid)
    chain = []
    node = uid
    loop do
      chain << node
      break if node == @guide_room_id

      info = @parent[node]
      break unless info && info[:from]

      node = info[:from]
    end
    chain
  end

  # Real number of moves between two arbitrary known rooms via their
  # lowest common ancestor in the @parent tree - nil if either isn't
  # connected to the map at all. Confirmed in the field: maybe_abandon_
  # for_closer_piece used to compare a candidate's distance-to-guide
  # against the player's own distance-to-guide, with no idea how far the
  # player would actually have to walk to reach the candidate in the
  # first place - a candidate "closer to the guide" in tree terms can
  # still be a long detour from wherever the player actually is, and
  # comparing the wrong two numbers like that made it possible to switch
  # back and forth between two pieces forever, never delivering either.
  def self.tree_distance(a, b)
    return 0 if a == b

    chain_a = ancestor_chain(a)
    chain_b = ancestor_chain(b)
    index_in_b = chain_b.each_with_index.to_h
    chain_a.each_with_index do |node, steps_from_a|
      steps_from_b = index_in_b[node]
      return steps_from_a + steps_from_b if steps_from_b
    end
    nil
  end

  def self.continue_transport
    @current_operation = :transporting
    descriptor = @transporting[:descriptor]
    uid = XMLData.room_id

    if uid == @guide_room_id
      # Confirmed in the field: DELIVERY_REGEX matching the guide's own
      # dialogue was the only thing that ever marked a piece :delivered -
      # when that text didn't match (wrong/incomplete wording), the piece
      # sat at :in_transit forever even though we'd genuinely kicked it all
      # the way into the guide's room, so @delivered stayed empty and
      # "run ended - delivered 0 piece(s)" printed despite real deliveries.
      # We already know we just kicked descriptor in here ourselves -
      # deliver() (now idempotent against double-counting) doesn't need to
      # wait on the guide's text to confirm what we just watched happen.
      deliver(descriptor)
      @transporting = nil
      return
    end

    # Confirmed in the field: another player sharing the room with the
    # piece we're pushing usually means they're already kicking the same
    # one - we'd otherwise just keep following it along, racing them with
    # no way to win since we only ever kick on our own turn. Treat the
    # piece as someone else's the moment we see this, log it, and move on
    # to whatever else is available (another part, exploration, an
    # obstacle) rather than keep chasing it. If it turns out the other
    # player actually delivers it, the existing DELIVERY_REGEX listener
    # still marks it :delivered correctly regardless of who kicked it in -
    # deliver() doesn't check who.
    if GameObj.pcs.any?
      @piece_location[descriptor] = uid
      @needed[descriptor] = :claimed
      @claimed_pieces[descriptor] = uid
      @piece_last_updated_at[descriptor] = Time.now.to_i
      @sync_dirty = true
      force_sync_publish!
      @transporting = nil
      say "#{descriptor} appears to be claimed by another player in room #{uid} - leaving it and moving on"
      return
    end

    back = @parent[uid] && @parent[uid][:back]
    unless back
      say "lost the way back to the guide room with #{descriptor} in tow, stopping transport"
      @transporting = nil
      return
    end

    obstacle = current_vines[back] || current_wards[back]
    if obstacle
      debug_say "an obstacle blocks #{back} while transporting #{descriptor} - destroying"
      destroy_obstacle(obstacle)
    end

    piece = GameObj.loot.find { |o| strip_article(o.name).downcase == descriptor }

    # Confirmed in the field: a piece we ourselves just kicked into this
    # exact room can still momentarily be missing from GameObj.loot - the
    # room's object list doesn't always finish populating before
    # wait_for_room_arrival's "Obvious paths" marker shows up (the kick that
    # carried it in landed before the object got added). Believing "lost
    # track" on that very first check would abandon a piece that's almost
    # certainly sitting right here - give the object list one more chance
    # to catch up with a fresh look before believing it's really gone. Only
    # the ONE check immediately following our own kick gets this grace -
    # @kick_arrival_uid is consumed (cleared) right after, so a genuinely
    # stale re-check later doesn't get an extra look every time.
    if !piece && @kick_arrival_uid == uid
      debug_say "#{descriptor} not seen yet right after kicking it in here - looking again before giving up"
      send_command('look')
      wait_for_room_arrival
      piece = GameObj.loot.find { |o| strip_article(o.name).downcase == descriptor }
    end
    @kick_arrival_uid = nil

    unless piece
      say "lost track of #{descriptor} in this room, re-scanning"
      # Remembered so merge_remote_pieces! doesn't immediately undo this by
      # re-adopting a teammate's still-stale :located claim for this exact
      # same descriptor+room - see @rejected_locations' declaration comment.
      @rejected_locations[descriptor] = { uid: uid, at: Time.now.to_i }
      @transporting = nil
      @needed[descriptor] = :needed
      @sync_dirty = true
      force_sync_publish!
      return
    end

    debug_say "kicking #{descriptor} #{back} from room #{uid}"
    # The kick has roundtime, and the *first* line back is always the
    # "you prepare to shove it" flavor text - which itself contains the
    # word "shove", so matching on push|shove right away (the old
    # approach) fired immediately on that line, before the real outcome
    # (success, "too dangerous," monster interrupt, etc.) had even been
    # decided server-side. Send the command once, then separately wait
    # out the roundtime and poll (without ever resending anything) for
    # whichever real outcome line shows up after it.
    send_command("kick #{kick_phrase(descriptor)} #{back}")
    wait_out_roundtime
    outcome = wait_for_kick_outcome
    debug_say "kick result: #{outcome.inspect}"

    if outcome == :danger
      if pacifist? && descriptor != @forced_piece
        # Still right here in room uid, just blocked from going further -
        # update memory and abandon it for now rather than fight. Next
        # tick's next_located_descriptor will pick something else (another
        # part, exploration, or obstacle-clearing) and come back to this
        # one later if nothing better turns up.
        @piece_location[descriptor] = uid
        @needed[descriptor] = :located
        @piece_last_updated_at[descriptor] = Time.now.to_i
        @sync_dirty = true
        force_sync_publish!
        @blocked_pieces[descriptor] = { room: uid, blocked_at: Time.now }
        @transporting = nil
        say "pacifist: #{descriptor} is blocked by a monster #{back} of room #{uid} - abandoning it for now"
        return
      end

      # descriptor == @forced_piece here (pacifist already announced and
      # flipped pacifist_combat_allowed back in next_located_descriptor the
      # moment every piece became blocked) - or pacifist is off entirely.
      # Either way, fall through to the normal response.
      wait_for_player_to_clear_room("too dangerous to push #{descriptor} #{back}")
      return
    end

    unless outcome == :success
      debug_say "kick didn't succeed (#{outcome.inspect}) - will retry next tick"
      return
    end

    if XMLData.room_id == uid
      # The shove didn't carry us along with it - follow it ourselves.
      move(back)
    else
      # Some kicks carry the player into the next room right along with
      # the piece. We're already there - moving "back" again would be
      # wrong (it may not even be a valid exit from here) - just make
      # sure the room's full description has finished arriving.
      debug_say "kick carried us straight into room #{XMLData.room_id} along with #{descriptor}"
      wait_for_room_arrival
    end

    on_room_entered(XMLData.room_id)

    # Grace flag for the very next continue_transport check in this room -
    # see its declaration comment above the "lost track" handling.
    @kick_arrival_uid = XMLData.room_id

    remaining = rooms_remaining_to_guide(XMLData.room_id)
    if remaining.nil?
      say "kicked #{descriptor} #{back} - lost track of how many rooms are left"
    elsif remaining.zero?
      say "kicked #{descriptor} into the guide's room"
    else
      say "kicked #{descriptor} #{back} - #{remaining} room#{'s' unless remaining == 1} left to the guide"
    end
  end

  ## ---- exploration (DFS with breadcrumb parent pointers) ----------------

  # Walks a single freshly-found exit and records it in @edges/@parent.
  # Shared by continue_exploration's normal forward step and
  # explore_new_exits below.
  # Returns [new_uid, already_known] - already_known is true if new_uid
  # had a @parent entry before this call, i.e. the maze looped back to a
  # room some other path already reached (this maze has cycles - the
  # ASCII overview shows grid-like loops, not a pure tree).
  def self.explore_exit(from_uid, direction)
    debug_say "room #{from_uid}: exploring #{direction}"
    move(direction) # blocks (pausing for the player) until it actually succeeds
    new_uid = XMLData.room_id
    record_edge(from_uid, direction, new_uid)
    already_known = !@parent[new_uid].nil?
    @parent[new_uid] ||= { from: from_uid, back: reverse_direction(direction) }
    on_room_entered(new_uid)
    [new_uid, already_known]
  end

  # Recursively explores every *freely walkable* exit this room has that
  # isn't already in @edges, then returns to this room - regardless of
  # whether it's the active DFS cursor. process_obstacle_queue calls this
  # right after destroying whatever was blocking a logged room, since the
  # directions it just opened up (extra_candidates) never show up in
  # short_exits/current_vines/current_wards on their own once the obstacle
  # is gone. Never re-includes current_vines/current_wards itself - any
  # *other* obstacle this reveal stumbles into gets logged by
  # handle_obstacles_on_entry (via on_room_entered, called from
  # explore_exit below) and queued for its own later pass, not chased
  # immediately.
  #
  # Only recurses into new_uid when it's genuinely brand new - a cycle
  # back to an already-visited room is just a new edge, not a new branch
  # to explore. And it walks back via reverse_direction(unexplored) - the
  # direction we actually just used - never via @parent[new_uid][:back],
  # which (on a cycle) can belong to a completely different path than the
  # one we took to get here, sending us off toward the wrong room instead
  # of back to where this loop started. That mismatch is what caused the
  # script to wander and lose track of where it was.
  def self.explore_new_exits(uid, extra_candidates = [])
    loop do
      # Both candidate_exits and the eventual "go explore that direction"
      # command only make sense if we're actually standing in uid right
      # now. If a previous iteration's return-trip move landed somewhere
      # else (a non-reciprocal exit - this maze isn't guaranteed to be
      # symmetric), continuing anyway would read the WRONG room's exits
      # as if they belonged to uid, sending nonsense directions and
      # quietly corrupting @edges from there on - which is exactly what
      # caused the script to wander in circles. Fail loudly instead so the
      # next tick recovers using wherever we actually are.
      if XMLData.room_id != uid
        raise "explore_new_exits: expected to be in room #{uid} but actually in #{XMLData.room_id}"
      end

      # extra_candidates first, not last - these are the direction(s) an
      # obstacle was just destroyed to open up, and the whole point of
      # passing them in is to explore them right away. Confirmed in the
      # field: with short_exits first, a room reached by a cyclical path
      # (this maze has confirmed cycles/non-reciprocal exits) can still
      # have one of its own *ordinary* cardinal exits genuinely unexplored
      # too (reaching the room from a different direction than the one
      # being explored here doesn't confirm this room's own exits) - that
      # ordinary exit's entire recursive subtree got explored first every
      # time, deferring the actually-just-revealed room arbitrarily long
      # behind it instead of "immediately."
      candidate_exits = (extra_candidates + short_exits).uniq
      unexplored = candidate_exits.find { |dir| @edges[uid][dir].nil? }
      break unless unexplored

      new_uid, already_known = explore_exit(uid, unexplored)
      explore_new_exits(new_uid) unless already_known
      move(reverse_direction(unexplored))
    end
  end

  # Works through @obstacle_rooms - rooms logged by handle_obstacles_on_
  # entry during free exploration - one at a time. Peeks rather than shifts
  # up front so an interruption (e.g. check_for_available_piece! firing
  # mid-destroy) leaves the room at the front of the queue instead of
  # silently dropping it; only removed once its obstacles are confirmed
  # gone. Directions are captured *before* destroying anything because the
  # game doesn't push a fresh "Obvious paths"/compass update just because
  # an obstacle died - confirmed in the field: a vine covering northeast
  # was destroyed and the very next thing the script did was explore west,
  # never touching northeast at all.
  # uid is a leaf if nothing in @parent ever points back to it as a :from -
  # i.e. nothing branches further from it. The path from the guide room to
  # EVERY leaf, taken together, covers every room in the known map (every
  # room lies on the path to at least one of its own descendant leaves) -
  # so revisiting just the leaves re-triggers on_room_entered/handle_
  # obstacles_on_entry everywhere we've ever been, without needing a
  # separate navigate_to per room.
  def self.leaf_rooms
    children = Hash.new(0)
    @parent.each_value { |info| children[info[:from]] += 1 if info[:from] }
    @parent.keys.select { |uid| children[uid].zero? }
  end

  # Confirmed in the field: pieces can end up permanently "needed -
  # location unknown" even after the whole known map is explored and every
  # logged obstacle cleared, if something blocking a passage was never
  # recognized as an obstacle at all (e.g. haze, before it was added to
  # all_vines/all_wards/current_vines/current_wards) - that exit just
  # silently never made it into candidate_exits, and once @fully_explored
  # flips true the DFS never revisits anywhere to notice. Revisits every
  # leaf room so handle_obstacles_on_entry gets another look at everywhere
  # we've ever been and picks up anything that wasn't recognized the first
  # time, then resumes obstacle-clearing if it finds something new. Called
  # from tick's idle branch only when truly stuck (fully explored, still
  # missing pieces, nothing else to do) - returns whether it actually
  # found anything new, so that branch knows whether to expect work on the
  # next tick.
  def self.resweep_for_missed_obstacles!
    return false if @last_resweep_at && (Time.now - @last_resweep_at) < RESWEEP_COOLDOWN_SECONDS

    @last_resweep_at = Time.now
    before = @obstacle_rooms.size
    leaves = leaf_rooms
    debug_say "still missing pieces with nothing left to explore - resweeping #{leaves.size} leaf room(s) for obstacles that weren't recognized the first time"

    leaves.each { |uid| navigate_to(uid) }
    navigate_to(@guide_room_id)

    found = @obstacle_rooms.size - before
    if found > 0
      say "resweep found #{found} obstacle room#{'s' unless found == 1} that weren't caught the first time - resuming obstacle-clearing"
      @phase = :clearing_obstacles
      @fully_explored = false
      true
    else
      debug_say "resweep found nothing new"
      false
    end
  end

  # Drives tick's dispatch while ";inqui blocks" is in effect - room-block
  # clearing (and the exploration needed to find more of them) takes
  # priority over everything except a genuinely *new* piece turning up
  # (handle_blocks snapshots @blocks_known_descriptors at activation time,
  # so re-finding whatever was already known - including whatever was just
  # dropped to start this directive - doesn't end it early). A new piece
  # immediately ends the directive and resumes normal pickup. Returns true
  # if it did something; false once there's truly nothing left to explore
  # or clear, at which point it deactivates itself and lets tick fall
  # through to its normal dispatch in the same call.
  def self.blocks_directive_tick
    descriptor = next_located_descriptor
    descriptor = nil if descriptor && @blocks_known_descriptors.include?(descriptor)

    if descriptor
      @blocks_directive_active = false
      say "a new part is locatable - resuming normal pickup"
      begin_transport(descriptor)
      return true
    end

    if @obstacle_rooms.any?
      @phase = :clearing_obstacles
      process_obstacle_queue
      return true
    end

    if !@fully_explored
      continue_exploration
      return true
    end

    @blocks_directive_active = false
    debug_say "blocks directive: nothing left to explore or clear - resuming normal handling"
    false
  end

  def self.process_obstacle_queue
    @current_operation = :exploring
    if @obstacle_rooms.empty?
      debug_say "all logged obstacles cleared - maze considered fully explored"
      @fully_explored = true
      return
    end

    uid = @obstacle_rooms.find { |u| !(group_sync_enabled? && remote_claim_fresh?(u)) }
    unless uid
      debug_say "all logged obstacles are claimed by teammates right now - nothing to do this tick"
      return
    end

    @sync_dirty = true
    force_sync_publish! # claim this room before walking to it, so a teammate doesn't pick it too
    navigate_to(uid)

    obstacles = all_vines + all_wards
    if obstacles.empty?
      debug_say "room #{uid} obstacles already gone (cleared incidentally earlier) - dropping from queue"
      @obstacle_rooms.delete(uid)
      @recently_cleared_obstacles = (@recently_cleared_obstacles + [uid]).last(RECENTLY_CLEARED_CAP)
      @obstacle_skip_streak = 0
      @sync_dirty = true
      force_sync_publish!
      return
    end

    # pacifist: a hostile sharing the room with the obstacle never gets
    # fought through here the way it does for a kick (the game won't
    # reject "kill #id" the way it rejects a kick, so InquiConundrum would
    # otherwise just attack the obstacle while ignoring the hostile - see
    # inky.lic). Abandon this block and rotate to another logged one,
    # unless every single one of them has already been tried this pass -
    # then clear this one anyway rather than stall forever.
    if pacifist? && hostile_present?
      if @obstacle_skip_streak < @obstacle_rooms.size - 1
        debug_say "room #{uid} has a hostile present and pacifist is on - abandoning this block for now, trying another"
        # Move uid (not necessarily @obstacle_rooms.first - the claim
        # filter above may have skipped past already-claimed rooms ahead
        # of it) to the back, rather than a blind rotate! that would
        # rotate starting from position 0 regardless of where uid is.
        @obstacle_rooms.delete(uid)
        @obstacle_rooms.push(uid)
        @obstacle_skip_streak += 1
        return
      end

      # Every logged obstacle has a hostile present - pacifist allows
      # clearing this one rather than stalling forever. Flip the shared
      # flag inky.lic (or any other combat-assist script) reads, so it
      # knows clearing this one is actually sanctioned.
      settings[:pacifist_combat_allowed] = true
      say "Pacifism can only attained through aggression! KILL!!!"
    end

    # Captured *before* destroying anything, same reasoning as ever - once
    # an obstacle's dead, GameObj.loot drops it and Obvious paths still
    # won't mention the direction it was covering, so this is the only
    # place that direction is ever visible. Keyed by id (not the GameObj
    # instance itself) since current_vines/current_wards and all_vines/
    # all_wards come from separate GameObj.loot scans - nothing guarantees
    # they hand back the same object instances for the same in-game thing.
    id_to_dir = {}
    current_vines.merge(current_wards).each { |dir, obj| id_to_dir[obj.id] = dir }

    # Confirmed in the field: blindly trusting every kill to have worked
    # and force-feeding every direction into explore_new_exits regardless
    # sent it walking into a direction that was actually still blocked - a
    # vine-tangled solid rock wall gave up after 3 unclear outcomes while
    # still standing, and explore_exit's move(:e) then retried "You can't
    # go there" forever, since move's own retry-forever loop has no escape
    # for a direction that's never going to open. Only a direction whose
    # obstacle destroy_obstacle actually confirmed destroyed/gone gets
    # force-fed in now.
    opened_directions = []
    all_cleared = true
    obstacles.each do |obstacle|
      cleared = destroy_obstacle(obstacle)
      all_cleared &&= cleared
      dir = id_to_dir[obstacle.id]
      opened_directions << dir if cleared && dir
    end

    @obstacle_skip_streak = 0
    if all_cleared
      @obstacle_rooms.delete(uid)
      @recently_cleared_obstacles = (@recently_cleared_obstacles + [uid]).last(RECENTLY_CLEARED_CAP)
      @sync_dirty = true
      force_sync_publish!
    else
      debug_say "room #{uid} still has an obstacle standing after giving up on it - leaving queued to retry later"
    end

    @current_operation = :exploring
    explore_new_exits(uid, opened_directions.uniq) if opened_directions.any?
  end

  def self.continue_exploration
    @current_operation = :exploring
    # A piece delivery shortcuts straight back to the guide room via
    # navigate_to, skipping the normal one-step-at-a-time backtrack that
    # would otherwise re-check every ancestor room along the way. Walk back
    # to wherever the DFS actually left off before resuming it, so the
    # guide room being "exhausted" doesn't get mistaken for the whole maze
    # being exhausted.
    if @exploration_cursor && XMLData.room_id != @exploration_cursor
      debug_say "returning to exploration cursor room #{@exploration_cursor} from #{XMLData.room_id}"
      navigate_to(@exploration_cursor)
    end

    uid = XMLData.room_id
    @exploration_cursor = uid

    # Freely-walkable exits only - a vine/ward-blocked direction never
    # shows up in short_exits at all ("Obvious paths" omits it even though
    # the room description names the exact direction it's blocking), so
    # this naturally skips them without needing to filter anything out.
    # Obstacle rooms get logged by handle_obstacles_on_entry instead and
    # worked through afterward by process_obstacle_queue, once every
    # freely-reachable room here has actually been visited - see the
    # @phase switch below.
    candidate_exits = short_exits
    unexplored = candidate_exits.find { |dir| @edges[uid][dir].nil? }

    if unexplored
      @exploration_cursor, = explore_exit(uid, unexplored)
    elsif uid == @guide_room_id
      if @obstacle_rooms.empty?
        debug_say "guide room has no unexplored exits left and no logged obstacles - maze considered fully explored"
        @fully_explored = true
      else
        debug_say "free exploration exhausted - switching to clearing #{@obstacle_rooms.size} logged obstacle room(s)"
        @phase = :clearing_obstacles
      end
    else
      back = @parent[uid] && @parent[uid][:back]
      if back
        debug_say "room #{uid} exhausted, backtracking #{back}"
        move(back)
        @exploration_cursor = XMLData.room_id
        # Without this, @last_room_id never updates for a backtrack step,
        # so the next tick's "did the player move us" check in tick
        # misfires - it thinks something else moved us into this (already
        # fully-explored) room and re-scans/re-decides to backtrack again,
        # producing a confusing "room changed without the script moving
        # us" message for a move the script itself just made.
        on_room_entered(@exploration_cursor)
      else
        @fully_explored = true
      end
    end
  end

  ## ---- run lifecycle -------------------------------------------------------

  def self.maybe_start_run
    # ZONE_REGEX (not just START_ROOM_REGEX) so we start working - logging
    # parts, clearing traps - the moment we're dropped anywhere in the
    # zone, rather than sitting idle until manually walked to the guide.
    # Wherever we land becomes a provisional anchor; on_room_entered
    # re-roots onto the guide's real room as soon as exploration finds it.
    return unless XMLData.room_title =~ ZONE_REGEX

    @in_run         = true
    @guide_room_id  = XMLData.room_id
    @guide_room_confirmed = false
    @last_guide_status_check_at = nil
    @run_started_at = Time.now
    @rooms_moved_since_run_start = 0
    @needed         = {}
    @seen           = {}
    @piece_location = {}
    @transporting   = nil
    @kick_arrival_uid = nil
    @delivered      = []
    @claimed_pieces = {}
    @edges          = Hash.new { |h, k| h[k] = {} }
    @parent         = { @guide_room_id => { from: nil, back: nil } }
    @exploration_cursor = nil
    @phase          = :exploring_free
    @obstacle_rooms = []
    @trap_rooms     = []
    @recently_cleared_traps = []
    @all_known      = false
    @fully_explored = false
    @parsing_status = false
    @idle_announced = false
    @last_location_report = nil
    @last_status_update_at = nil
    @surrender_triggered = false
    @current_operation = :idle
    @fetching_descriptor = nil
    @blocked_pieces = {}
    @forced_piece = nil
    @obstacle_skip_streak = 0
    @last_resweep_at = nil
    @blocks_directive_active = false
    @blocks_known_descriptors = []
    @last_sync_publish_at = nil
    @sync_dirty = false
    @remote_claims = {}
    @remote_claims_by_char = {}
    @piece_last_updated_at = {}
    @recently_cleared_obstacles = []
    @sync_scope_for_run = nil
    @sync_force_pending = false
    @rejected_locations = {}

    # Inky (or any other combat-assist script) reads this directly out of
    # UserVars rather than calling into this module - same independence
    # inky.lic's own VINE_REGEX/WARD_REGEX copies are kept for. Not an
    # OPTION_KEYS entry - it's derived run state, not something ;inqui set
    # should ever take directly from the player.
    settings[:pacifist_combat_allowed] = !pacifist?

    say "run started in #{XMLData.room_title}"
    say "PACIFIST RUN! KIL.... err.. peeeeace.... ehh." if pacifist?
    debug_say "provisional anchor room id = #{@guide_room_id}"

    # Frozen for the whole run, never recomputed live from Group.members -
    # a mid-run roster change would otherwise silently switch which shared
    # DB row this character reads/writes, orphaning everything already
    # published under the old scope.
    if group_sync_enabled?
      @sync_scope_for_run = compute_sync_scope
      Settings.refresh_data(@sync_scope_for_run)
      shared = Settings.root_proxy_for(@sync_scope_for_run)
      started_at = shared['run_started_at']
      if started_at.nil? || (Time.now.to_i - started_at.to_i) > MAX_RUN_SECONDS
        debug_say "group sync: shared run state for scope #{@sync_scope_for_run} is stale or absent - resetting"
        shared['run_started_at'] = Time.now.to_i
        shared['slices'] = {}
      end
    end

    on_room_entered(@guide_room_id)
  end

  def self.maybe_end_run
    return unless @in_run

    ended_by_room = !!(XMLData.room_title =~ END_ROOM_REGEX)
    ended_by_surrender = @surrender_triggered
    return unless ended_by_room || ended_by_surrender || (Time.now - @run_started_at) > MAX_RUN_SECONDS

    run_duration = Time.now - @run_started_at

    say "run ended - delivered #{@delivered.size} piece(s): #{@delivered.join(', ')}"
    debug_say(if ended_by_room
                "ended: exit room title matched"
              elsif ended_by_surrender
                "ended: surrendermania surrendered"
              else
                "ended: MAX_RUN_SECONDS timeout reached"
              end)

    say "surrender run time: #{format_duration(run_duration)}" if ended_by_surrender

    # A timeout means the script gave up, not a real completion - doesn't
    # belong in "best" time tracking alongside actual finishes.
    unless !ended_by_room && !ended_by_surrender
      best = settings[:best_run_seconds]
      if best.nil? || run_duration < best
        settings[:best_run_seconds] = run_duration
        say "new best run time: #{format_duration(run_duration)}"
      end
    end

    # Whatever this character published for this run (edges, obstacle
    # rooms, piece locations, claims) is about to go stale the moment the
    # next run starts - clear it now rather than leaving it for a
    # teammate's very next merge to pick up and get confused by. Confirmed
    # in the field: a follow-up run starting soon after the last one ended
    # (the normal repeatevent case) never tripped maybe_start_run's own
    # staleness check, since "soon after" is never older than
    # MAX_RUN_SECONDS - so the previous run's stale slice just sat there
    # and got merged straight into the fresh run.
    clear_sync_state_for_completed_run!

    @in_run = false
    @transporting = nil
    @surrender_triggered = false
    @completions += 1

    if repeat_event?
      say "Completed run - #{@completions} total completions"
      requeue_for_next_run
    else
      # repeatevent is off - stop dead in the post-ejection room. Never walk
      # back toward the arena on our own; that's requeue_for_next_run's job
      # only, and only when repeatevent is on. Literal pause_script (not
      # just idling in main_loop) so the player has to explicitly opt back
      # in, instead of the script silently re-arming itself the moment
      # ZONE_REGEX happens to match again (e.g. just walking through on
      # the way somewhere else).
      say "repeatevent is off - stopping here. Run ;unpause inquiconundrum when you're ready to go again."
      pause_script
      sleep 0.2 while Script.current.paused?
      debug_say "unpaused, resuming"
    end
  end

  # running?()'s loose start-anchored fallback match would also catch
  # something like a hypothetical go2-prefixed script name - exact match
  # only, same reasoning as inky.lic's bigshot_running?.
  def self.go2_running?
    Script.running.any? { |s| s.name =~ /^go2$/i } || Script.hidden.any? { |s| s.name =~ /^go2$/i }
  end

  # go2 can get muckled/stuck waiting on a confirmation prompt - bounded
  # wait so a stuck go2 doesn't strand requeue_for_next_run (and therefore
  # the whole repeatevent loop) forever.
  def self.run_go2_to_arena
    start_script('go2', [ARENA_MAGISTER_UID])
    pause 0.2 # give Script.start a moment to register before polling for it

    deadline = Time.now + GO2_TIMEOUT_SECONDS
    while go2_running?
      if Time.now > deadline
        say "go2 #{ARENA_MAGISTER_UID} didn't finish within #{GO2_TIMEOUT_SECONDS}s - giving up waiting, continuing anyway"
        break
      end
      pause 0.2
    end
  end

  # Walks back from the post-ejection room to the Arena Magister (via go2)
  # and asks for entry twice (the second confirms entering without an
  # aevarch), putting us back into the minigame. Only called when
  # repeatevent is on.
  #
  # A follower needs to be physically present to get pulled into the new
  # run (confirmed - entry isn't group-wide regardless of location), but
  # never travels or asks the magister independently - they only ever
  # "join" the leader (see regroup_with_leader_then_return_to_arena) and
  # get dragged along as the leader walks and asks for both. Asking twice
  # themselves on top of that would be redundant at best and risks a
  # "you must wait" rejection at worst.
  def self.requeue_for_next_run
    following = group_sync_enabled? && !Group.leader?
    Script.pause(INKY_SCRIPT) if following

    begin
      send_command('stow hands')
      send_command('get package')
      pause 1
      send_command('stow hands')
      send_command('gird')

      if group_sync_enabled?
        regroup_with_leader_then_return_to_arena
      else
        run_go2_to_arena
      end

      unless following
        pause 1
        send_command('ask magister about entry')
        pause 1
        send_command('ask magister about entry')
      end
    ensure
      # Always attempt the unpause, even if something above raised - a
      # follower stuck with inky permanently paused would otherwise have
      # no combat assist for the rest of the session.
      wait_for_new_event_then_unpause_inky if following
    end
  end

  # A follower has nothing useful to fight while being dragged along
  # mid-regroup - inky stays paused for the whole requeue_for_next_run
  # stretch (stow/gird/join/walk/ask-for-entry) and only resumes once
  # NEW_EVENT_START_ROOM_UID confirms the new run has actually begun.
  # Bounded the same way run_go2_to_arena is - inky shouldn't stay paused
  # forever just because this character never actually arrived.
  def self.wait_for_new_event_then_unpause_inky
    deadline = Time.now + GO2_TIMEOUT_SECONDS
    until XMLData.room_id.to_s == NEW_EVENT_START_ROOM_UID
      if Time.now > deadline
        debug_say "never saw room #{NEW_EVENT_START_ROOM_UID} within #{GO2_TIMEOUT_SECONDS}s - unpausing #{INKY_SCRIPT} anyway"
        break
      end
      pause 0.5
    end
    Script.unpause(INKY_SCRIPT)
  end

  # Grouped: only the leader ever navigates - a follower never independently
  # go2's to the arena and never asks the magister themselves (confirmed:
  # entry requires physically being in the room, but the leader walking
  # there with the group already in tow, then asking, is what actually gets
  # everyone in - a follower racing there on their own just risks scattering
  # the group again right after finally regrouping). A follower only ever
  # "join"s the leader, right here in the post-ejection room, and is then
  # fully along for whatever the leader does next - no fallback go2, ever,
  # even if leader_name can't be determined or the join doesn't seem to be
  # taking. wait_for_new_event_then_unpause_inky's own timeout is the only
  # safety net for "this character never actually made it in."
  def self.regroup_with_leader_then_return_to_arena
    if Group.leader?
      debug_say "group sync: leading - waiting up to #{REGROUP_TIMEOUT_SECONDS}s for the group to join up before heading back"
      pause REGROUP_TIMEOUT_SECONDS
      run_go2_to_arena
      return
    end

    leader = Group.leader
    leader_name = leader.respond_to?(:noun) ? leader.noun : nil
    unless leader_name
      debug_say "group sync: couldn't determine the group leader - nothing to join, waiting for the new run to start on its own"
      return
    end

    say "joining #{leader_name} to follow back to the arena"
    send_command("join #{leader_name}")
  end

  # A room only has a usable path back to the guide room if the DFS
  # actually reached it - navigate_to has nothing to walk otherwise.
  def self.reachable?(uid)
    uid == @guide_room_id || !@parent[uid].nil?
  end

  # pacifist: still considered blocked if it's on @blocked_pieces and
  # PACIFIST_BLOCKED_RETRY_SECONDS hasn't passed since it was abandoned -
  # the monster that blocked it might easily be long gone by now, so a
  # stale entry doesn't get to deprioritize it forever.
  def self.pacifist_blocked?(descriptor)
    blocked = @blocked_pieces[descriptor]
    return false unless blocked

    (Time.now - blocked[:blocked_at]) < PACIFIST_BLOCKED_RETRY_SECONDS
  end

  # Flips any :claimed piece whose CLAIMED_RETRY_SECONDS window has
  # elapsed back to :located, so next_located_descriptor's normal :located
  # selection picks it up again - the other player may never come back,
  # and there's no other code path that ever revisits a :claimed entry.
  # @piece_last_updated_at already gets stamped at the moment a piece is
  # marked :claimed (continue_transport), so it doubles as "claimed at"
  # here with no extra bookkeeping needed.
  def self.recheck_stale_claims!
    @needed.each do |descriptor, status|
      next unless status == :claimed

      claimed_at = @piece_last_updated_at[descriptor]
      age = claimed_at ? Time.now.to_i - claimed_at : Float::INFINITY

      # Every possible player here is a teammate also running this script -
      # trust their own claim publish over a flat timer once it's actually
      # had a chance to land (CLAIMED_GROUP_SYNC_GRACE_SECONDS). Recovers a
      # piece the moment the teammate's own next sync shows they're no
      # longer working it, instead of always waiting out the full
      # CLAIMED_RETRY_SECONDS regardless of what's actually still true.
      if group_sync_enabled? && age >= CLAIMED_GROUP_SYNC_GRACE_SECONDS && !remote_claim_fresh?(descriptor)
        debug_say "#{descriptor}: group sync shows no teammate currently claims this - reconsidering it now"
        @needed[descriptor] = :located
        next
      end

      next unless age >= CLAIMED_RETRY_SECONDS

      debug_say "#{descriptor}: claimed-by-another-player retry window elapsed - reconsidering it"
      @needed[descriptor] = :located
    end
  end

  def self.next_located_descriptor
    recheck_stale_claims!
    candidates = @needed.select { |d, status| status == :located && reachable?(@piece_location[d]) }.keys
    candidates = candidates.reject { |d| group_sync_enabled? && remote_claim_fresh?(d) }
    return closest_by_distance(candidates) unless pacifist?

    # pacifist: anything not currently blocked by a monster takes priority
    # over anything that is, no matter what - exploration/obstacle-clearing
    # already wins by virtue of running whenever this returns nil. A
    # piece's retry timer elapsing makes it count as unblocked again here
    # too - it's just a normal pickup attempt at that point, not the
    # @forced_piece combat fallback below, and never interrupts an actual
    # return-part job to happen, since this is only ever consulted while
    # @transporting is nil to begin with. Ranked by distance the same as
    # the non-pacifist case - among whichever pieces are currently
    # eligible (never blocked, or blocked but past its retry timer), the
    # closest one always wins.
    unblocked = candidates.reject { |d| pacifist_blocked?(d) }
    if unblocked.any?
      @forced_piece = nil
      return closest_by_distance(unblocked)
    end

    return nil if candidates.empty?

    # Confirmed in the field: forcing combat the moment the only one or two
    # announced pieces happen to be blocked was too eager - there was still
    # plenty of unexplored map and unlogged obstacles left to try instead,
    # which would likely have turned up an unblocked piece anyway. Below
    # the threshold, just return nil here - same as "nothing located at
    # all" - so exploration/obstacle-clearing runs instead, and don't
    # disturb @forced_piece (no transition has actually happened yet).
    if @needed.size < PACIFIST_FORCE_MIN_ANNOUNCED
      debug_say "pacifist: #{candidates.size} located piece(s) blocked, but only #{@needed.size} announced so far (need #{PACIFIST_FORCE_MIN_ANNOUNCED}) - exploring/clearing instead of forcing combat"
      return nil
    end

    # Every :located piece is blocked - pacifist still allows pushing
    # through combat for exactly one of them rather than stalling forever.
    # continue_transport checks @forced_piece to tell this case apart from
    # the normal "blocked, abandon it" pacifist response. Only announce on
    # the actual transition into this state, not every single tick it
    # stays true while @forced_piece's kick is still being retried/paused.
    forced = closest_by_distance(candidates)
    if @forced_piece != forced
      @forced_piece = forced
      settings[:pacifist_combat_allowed] = true
      say "Pacifism can only attained through aggression! KILL!!!"
    end
    @forced_piece
  end

  # "Always err to return parts closest to the guide" - applies even
  # mid-transport, pacifist on or off: if a piece announced (and already
  # known-located) while we're pushing a different one turns out to be
  # closer to the guide than wherever we currently are, abandon the
  # current piece right here (same bookkeeping pacifist's own "blocked,
  # abandon it" path uses) and let the dispatch below pick the closer one
  # up via next_located_descriptor instead. Checked once at the top of
  # tick, never mid-kick - continue_transport already sent (or is about
  # to send) at most one "kick" command per tick, so there's no in-flight
  # server response this could land on top of and desync from.
  def self.maybe_abandon_for_closer_piece
    return unless @transporting

    current_descriptor = @transporting[:descriptor]
    current_room = XMLData.room_id
    current_distance = distance_to_guide(current_room)

    alternatives = @needed.select { |d, status| status == :located && reachable?(@piece_location[d]) }.keys
    alternatives = alternatives.reject { |d| pacifist_blocked?(d) } if pacifist?
    alternatives = alternatives.reject { |d| group_sync_enabled? && remote_claim_fresh?(d) }
    return if alternatives.empty?

    # Total cost of switching: walk from here to the alternative's room,
    # then push it the rest of the way home - not just the alternative's
    # own distance-to-guide, which says nothing about how far out of the
    # way it actually is from here. Comparing that alone is what let this
    # flip back and forth between two pieces forever (see tree_distance).
    costed = alternatives.map { |d| [d, tree_distance(current_room, @piece_location[d])] }
                          .reject { |_, travel| travel.nil? }
                          .map { |d, travel| [d, travel + distance_to_guide(@piece_location[d])] }
    return if costed.empty?

    closest, closest_cost = costed.min_by { |_, cost| cost }
    return unless closest_cost < current_distance

    @piece_location[current_descriptor] = current_room
    @needed[current_descriptor] = :located
    @transporting = nil
    say "#{closest} is a better pickup from here (#{closest_cost} room#{'s' unless closest_cost == 1} total) than finishing #{current_descriptor} (#{current_distance} room#{'s' unless current_distance == 1} left) - abandoning #{current_descriptor} here to go get it instead"
  end

  # Room number for whatever's left (anything not yet :delivered), with
  # whichever location we've got for it - last :located room, otherwise
  # the last room it was ever seen in, otherwise unknown entirely.
  def self.debug_report_remaining_parts
    remaining = @needed.reject { |_, status| status == :delivered }
    return if remaining.empty?

    remaining.each do |descriptor, status|
      location = @piece_location[descriptor] || @seen[descriptor]
      where = location ? "room #{location}" : "location unknown"
      debug_say "remaining: #{descriptor} (#{status}) - #{where}"
    end
  end

  # Only pieces the guide has actually announced (@needed, minus ones
  # already :delivered) - @seen on its own holds every part ever logged
  # (dozens, most irrelevant), which used to get dumped here wholesale.
  # Printed (not debug-gated) while idle so the player can walk out and
  # manually grab anything the script can't currently reach or move itself
  # (e.g. stuck behind something it can't clear). Deduped against the last
  # report so it doesn't reprint every 2 seconds while waiting.
  def self.report_known_part_locations
    wanted = @needed.reject { |_, status| status == :delivered }.keys
    located = wanted.select { |d| @seen.key?(d) }
    return if located.empty?

    lines = located.map { |d| "u#{@seen[d]}: #{d}" }.sort
    report = lines.join('; ')
    return if report == @last_location_report

    @last_location_report = report
    say "known part locations (investigate any that are stuck):"
    lines.each { |line| say "  #{line}" }
  end

  # "Remaining" was never a real number - @needed only contains pieces the
  # guide has announced SO FAR, and more keep arriving until @all_known, so
  # @needed.size - delivered is a constantly shifting denominator, not a
  # real total. Reports each announced piece individually instead (its
  # status and, if known, room) plus what's currently being done about it.
  # Time left is this script's own MAX_RUN_SECONDS budget, not a
  # game-confirmed figure - the TIME_WARNING_REGEX listener already relays
  # the game's own warnings verbatim when they arrive.
  def self.report_status_now
    unless @in_run
      say "status: no run currently active - waiting to be placed in the zone."
      say "completions this session: #{@completions}"
      say "best run time: #{best_run_time_description}"
      return
    end

    minutes_left = [(MAX_RUN_SECONDS - (Time.now - @run_started_at)) / 60, 0].max.round
    say "status: #{@seen.size} part#{'s' unless @seen.size == 1} logged in memory, ~#{minutes_left} minute#{'s' unless minutes_left == 1} left"
    say "Still waiting on more part announcements" unless @all_known

    if @needed.empty?
      say "no pieces announced yet"
    else
      @needed.each do |descriptor, status|
        if status == :delivered
          say "  #{descriptor}: delivered"
        else
          location = @piece_location[descriptor] || @seen[descriptor]
          if location
            distance = rooms_remaining_to_guide(location)
            where = distance ? "room #{location} (#{distance} room#{'s' unless distance == 1} from guide)" : "room #{location} (unreachable)"
          else
            where = "location unknown"
          end
          blocked = pacifist_blocked?(descriptor) ? " (blocked by a monster - pacifist)" : ""
          say "  #{descriptor}: #{status} - #{where}#{blocked}"
        end
      end
    end

    say "current operation: #{current_operation_description}"
    say "completions this session: #{@completions}"
    say "best run time: #{best_run_time_description}"
  end

  # Throttled to STATUS_UPDATE_INTERVAL_SECONDS so it summarizes progress
  # periodically while idle instead of spamming every tick.
  def self.maybe_report_status
    now = Time.now
    return if @last_status_update_at && (now - @last_status_update_at) < STATUS_UPDATE_INTERVAL_SECONDS

    @last_status_update_at = now
    report_status_now
  end

  # Shared by report_status_now and the every-3-rooms progress ping, so
  # both describe "what am I doing right now" identically.
  def self.current_operation_description
    case @current_operation
    when :destroying_obstacle
      "destroying room blockers"
    when :fetching
      "fetching #{@fetching_descriptor}"
    when :transporting
      descriptor = @transporting && @transporting[:descriptor]
      if descriptor
        remaining = rooms_remaining_to_guide(XMLData.room_id)
        if remaining
          "returning #{descriptor} to guide, #{remaining} room#{'s' unless remaining == 1} left"
        else
          "returning #{descriptor} to guide"
        end
      else
        "waiting on next announcement"
      end
    when :exploring
      "exploring rooms"
    else
      "waiting on next announcement"
    end
  end

  def self.format_duration(seconds)
    total = seconds.to_i
    minutes, secs = total.divmod(60)
    "#{minutes}m #{secs}s"
  end

  # settings[:best_run_seconds] persists across sessions (per character) -
  # a personal best should survive a relog, not just last this process.
  def self.best_run_time_description
    best = settings[:best_run_seconds]
    best ? format_duration(best) : 'none yet'
  end

  # Called from on_room_entered every time a room actually changes -
  # surfaces what the script is doing/how long it's been going without
  # the player having to type ;inqui status themselves.
  ROOM_PROGRESS_OPERATION_INTERVAL = 3
  ROOM_PROGRESS_ELAPSED_INTERVAL = 10

  def self.report_room_progress
    return unless @in_run

    if (@rooms_moved_since_run_start % ROOM_PROGRESS_OPERATION_INTERVAL).zero?
      say "[#{@rooms_moved_since_run_start} rooms moved] current operation: #{current_operation_description}"
    end

    if (@rooms_moved_since_run_start % ROOM_PROGRESS_ELAPSED_INTERVAL).zero?
      say "[#{@rooms_moved_since_run_start} rooms moved] time elapsed: #{format_duration(Time.now - @run_started_at)}"
    end
  end

  # ;inqui reset - manual recovery: walk back to the guide room (abandoning
  # any piece currently mid-transport, since walking doesn't bring a piece
  # along - only kicking does), report status, wait 5 seconds, then re-ask
  # the guide for its current list of needed pieces. Doesn't otherwise touch
  # @needed/@seen - tick's existing priority order (transport > located >
  # explore) already heads for any known piece first on the very next tick,
  # so there's nothing extra to do to "proceed to any known first."
  def self.handle_reset
    unless @in_run
      say "reset: no run currently active"
      return
    end

    if @transporting
      descriptor = @transporting[:descriptor]
      @needed[descriptor] = @piece_location[descriptor] ? :located : :needed
      @transporting = nil
      debug_say "reset: abandoned in-progress transport of #{descriptor}"
    end

    say "reset: heading back to the guide"
    # reset overrides everything, including a piece becoming available
    # mid-walk - without this, check_for_available_piece! could interrupt
    # this very walk back to the guide (the moment @transporting clears
    # above, any already-:located piece looks fair game again).
    @suppress_piece_interrupt = true
    begin
      navigate_to(@guide_room_id)
    ensure
      @suppress_piece_interrupt = false
    end
    report_status_now

    say "waiting for 5 seconds"
    pause 5

    send_command('ask guide about status')
  end

  # ";inqui blocks" - drop whatever's in progress and prioritize room-block
  # clearing (and the exploration needed to find more of them) over
  # everything else, until a genuinely new part turns up - see
  # blocks_directive_tick, which actually drives this each tick.
  def self.handle_blocks
    unless @in_run
      say "blocks: no run currently active"
      return
    end

    if @transporting
      descriptor = @transporting[:descriptor]
      uid = XMLData.room_id
      @piece_location[descriptor] = uid
      @needed[descriptor] = :located
      @transporting = nil
      debug_say "blocks: abandoned in-progress transport of #{descriptor}"
    end

    @blocks_known_descriptors = @needed.select { |_, status| status == :located }.keys
    @blocks_directive_active = true
    say "blocks: dropping everything to hunt down room blockers until a new part turns up"
  end

  # ";inqui return" - drop whatever's in progress and immediately start
  # kicking a different known, reachable part home. Unlike ";inqui blocks"
  # this is a one-shot pivot, not an ongoing directive - it just picks the
  # best located candidate right now (excluding whatever was just dropped,
  # so it doesn't pick the exact same part right back up).
  def self.handle_return
    unless @in_run
      say "return: no run currently active"
      return
    end

    dropped = nil
    if @transporting
      dropped = @transporting[:descriptor]
      uid = XMLData.room_id
      @piece_location[dropped] = uid
      @needed[dropped] = :located
      @transporting = nil
      debug_say "return: dropped in-progress transport of #{dropped}"
    end

    candidates = @needed.select { |d, status| status == :located && reachable?(@piece_location[d]) }.keys
    candidates -= [dropped] if dropped

    descriptor = closest_by_distance(candidates)
    unless descriptor
      if dropped
        say "CANNOT OBEY - This is the only part I know!"
      else
        say "CANNOT OBEY - I don't know where a part is!"
      end
      return
    end

    say "return: heading for #{descriptor} instead"
    begin_transport(descriptor)
  end

  # Commands intercepted by the upstream hook (see parse_upstream) land in
  # CMD_QUEUE; main_loop drains it and calls here. parse_upstream swallows
  # EVERY ";inquiconundrum ..."/";inqui ..." the player types while a run is
  # already active - not just "status" - so set/help (and a bare retry of
  # the start command itself) have to be handled here too, or they silently
  # fall through to "unrecognized message" instead of doing anything (and a
  # bare retry loses Lich's own "already running!" notice, since the hook
  # swallowed the command before Lich's dispatch ever saw it).
  def self.handle_command(msg)
    text = msg.to_s.strip
    case text
    when ''
      say "already running - try: status, set, help, reset, blocks, return"
    when /^status$/i
      report_status_now
    when /^set$/i
      show_settings
    when /^set\s+(.+)$/i
      handle_set($1.split(/\s+/))
    when /^help$/i
      show_settings
      respond(INQUICONUNDRUM_HELP)
    when /^reset$/i
      handle_reset
    when /^blocks$/i
      handle_blocks
    when /^return$/i
      handle_return
    else
      say "unrecognized message: '#{text}' (try: status, set, help, reset, blocks, return)"
    end
  end

  def self.tick
    maybe_end_run
    return unless @in_run

    # check_for_available_piece! (called via poll_background_events deep
    # inside continue_exploration's own recursive room-walking) raises this
    # the moment a piece becomes :located mid-exploration, rather than
    # waiting for that whole recursive dig to finish on its own - confirmed
    # in the field: it otherwise kept wandering for many more rooms past a
    # piece we already knew the location of. Just let this tick end early;
    # the next tick re-evaluates from scratch and picks next_located_
    # descriptor up normally below.
    begin
      # The player can move around manually too - while idle waiting on the
      # next announcement, during a combat pause, anywhere. Catch any room
      # change we didn't already scan ourselves so a part sitting in a room
      # the player walked into isn't permanently invisible to us.
      if XMLData.room_id != @last_room_id
        uid = XMLData.room_id
        debug_say "room changed to #{uid} without the script moving us there - scanning it"
        on_room_entered(uid)

        # scan_room will have marked anything needed here :located, but if
        # this room has no recorded path back to the guide room (the DFS
        # never actually reached it), navigate_to has nothing to walk and
        # would silently fail later. Flag it rather than let begin_transport
        # find that out the hard way.
        if @parent[uid].nil?
          debug_say "room #{uid} isn't connected to the known map - can't push anything home from here yet"
        end
      end

      sync_merge_remote_state! if group_sync_enabled?

      maybe_abandon_for_closer_piece

      if @transporting
        continue_transport
      elsif @blocks_directive_active && blocks_directive_tick
        # handled inside blocks_directive_tick
      elsif (descriptor = next_located_descriptor)
        begin_transport(descriptor)
      elsif !@fully_explored
        if @phase == :clearing_obstacles
          process_obstacle_queue
        else
          continue_exploration
        end
      else
        @current_operation = :idle
        debug_report_remaining_parts
        report_known_part_locations
        maybe_report_status

        still_needed  = @needed.select { |_, status| status == :needed }.keys
        unreachable   = @needed.select { |d, status| status == :located && !reachable?(@piece_location[d]) }.keys

        # A piece can fall back to :needed without ever really vanishing -
        # e.g. losing track of it mid-transport. If we've already seen it
        # somewhere, that's still our best lead: take another run at it
        # instead of waiting forever with a known location sitting unused.
        recoverable = still_needed.find { |d| @seen.key?(d) }
        if recoverable
          debug_say "re-attempting #{recoverable} from its last known room #{@seen[recoverable]}"
          @needed[recoverable] = :located
          @piece_location[recoverable] = @seen[recoverable]
        elsif still_needed.any? || unreachable.any?
          unreachable_desc = unreachable.map { |d| "#{d} (u#{@piece_location[d]})" }.join(', ')
          debug_say "fully explored with nothing deliverable; still missing: #{still_needed.join(', ')}; seen but unreachable: #{unreachable_desc}"
          resweep_for_missed_obstacles!
          pause 2
        else
          unless @idle_announced
            claimed = @needed.select { |_, status| status == :claimed }.keys
            if claimed.any?
              say "All currently announced pieces accounted for - #{claimed.size} claimed by another player (#{claimed.join(', ')}). Waiting on next announcement!"
            else
              say "All currently announced pieces delivered. Waiting on next announcement! Watch for monsters!"
            end
            say "Completed so far (#{@delivered.size}): #{@delivered.join(', ')}"
            @idle_announced = true
          end
          pause 2
        end
      end
    rescue PieceBecameAvailable
      debug_say "a piece's location just became known - abandoning exploration to go fetch it"
    rescue RunEnding
      debug_say "run is over - abandoning whatever action was in progress so maybe_end_run can actually end it"
    rescue StuckMove => e
      debug_say "#{e.message} - pivoting back to the main dispatch instead of repeating it"

      if @parent[e.uid] && @parent[e.uid][:back] == e.direction
        debug_say "room #{e.uid}'s recorded backtrack direction (#{e.direction}) doesn't actually work - this maze isn't always reciprocal. Clearing it so it isn't retried forever"
        @parent[e.uid][:back] = nil
      end
    ensure
      # Runs even when this tick ended via one of the rescues above - all
      # three (PieceBecameAvailable/RunEnding/StuckMove) are routine,
      # expected unwinds, not crashes, so whatever state was true at the
      # point of raise (a just-recorded edge, a freshly-set @transporting)
      # is still meaningful and worth a teammate seeing promptly.
      #
      # The only place sync_publish_local_state! is ever actually called -
      # this is always this script's own thread, never the DownstreamHook
      # thread force_sync_publish! can be triggered from (confirmed in the
      # field: a real Settings DB write happening directly on that thread
      # froze the entire client for minutes whenever it contended with the
      # other character's process). @sync_force_pending just carries
      # "something urgent happened" over to here, where it's safe to act
      # on it.
      if group_sync_enabled?
        sync_publish_local_state!(force: @sync_force_pending)
        @sync_force_pending = false
      end
    end
  end

  def self.main_loop
    loop do
      begin
        poll_background_events

        if @in_run
          tick
          # Floor on how fast this loop can ever spin. tick() normally
          # yields on its own (an fput's roundtime, a move, an explicit
          # pause elsewhere) - but a logic bug that lets it return without
          # ever sending anything to the game (confirmed in the field: a
          # piece location ping-ponging between :needed and :located with
          # group_sync re-adopting the same stale claim every merge) had
          # nothing else to slow it down, and produced 30,000+ log lines in
          # under a minute. This doesn't fix that kind of bug - it just
          # bounds the damage to ~20 ticks/sec instead of an unbounded tight
          # loop, whatever the cause.
          pause 0.05
        else
          maybe_start_run
          pause 1
        end
      rescue PieceBecameAvailable
        # Should normally be caught inside tick's own rescue - this is a
        # safety net for the rare path that can reach here uncaught instead
        # (e.g. ;inqui reset's own navigate_to walk, run via drain_cmd_queue
        # from outside tick entirely). Confirmed in the field: letting this
        # fall through to the generic StandardError handler below printed
        # the same error forever without ever resolving anything, since
        # nothing about the underlying condition changes between retries -
        # only tick's normal dispatch (on the very next loop iteration)
        # actually does that.
        debug_say "a piece's location became known outside tick - retrying"
      rescue RunEnding
        # Same safety net as PieceBecameAvailable above, for the same kind
        # of outside-tick path. Whichever case reaches here, @in_run is
        # still true and nothing has been changed yet - the very next loop
        # iteration's tick call runs maybe_end_run fresh and actually ends
        # it correctly.
        debug_say "run ending detected outside tick - retrying"
      rescue StuckMove => e
        # Same safety net as the other two above, for the same kind of
        # outside-tick path (e.g. ;inqui reset's or begin_transport's own
        # navigate_to walk). The very next loop iteration's tick call
        # re-dispatches fresh instead of repeating whatever was stuck.
        debug_say "#{e.message} - pivoting back to the main dispatch instead of repeating it"

        if @parent[e.uid] && @parent[e.uid][:back] == e.direction
          debug_say "room #{e.uid}'s recorded backtrack direction (#{e.direction}) doesn't actually work - this maze isn't always reciprocal. Clearing it so it isn't retried forever"
          @parent[e.uid][:back] = nil
        end
      rescue StandardError => e
        # An uncaught exception here would otherwise kill the script thread
        # silently - no pause message, no error, it just stops reacting.
        # Report it loudly instead of letting that happen invisibly.
        say "error in main loop: #{e.class}: #{e.message}"
        say e.backtrace.first(3).join(' | ') if e.backtrace
        pause 1
      end
    end
  end

  ## ---- multi-character cooperation (group_sync) --------------------------
  #
  # Two-plus characters, each running their own InquiConundrum.lic instance,
  # grouped together in-game, sharing the same local Lich DATA_DIR. Settings'
  # database_adapter.rb does a whole-row Marshal blob upsert keyed on
  # (script, scope) - confirmed by reading database_adapter.rb directly,
  # there is no partial/column-level update. Both processes run the literal
  # same script file, so Script.current.name (the "script" half of that key)
  # is identical between them - only the scope string (@sync_scope_for_run,
  # frozen once per run from the sorted group roster, see maybe_start_run)
  # separates "this group's shared state" from anything else. That
  # collapses the lost-update risk down to "two characters both writing the
  # SAME scope's blob" - avoided entirely by each character writing ONLY to
  # its own ['slices'][Char.name] leaf via a single SettingsProxy#[]= call.
  # save_proxy_changes (settings.rb) re-reads the fresh row before applying
  # a leaf write, so a single targeted leaf write is safe even if a
  # teammate's own leaf write lands concurrently.
  #
  # HARD RULE: no method outside this quartet - sync_publish_local_state!,
  # sync_merge_remote_state!, clear_sync_state_for_completed_run!, and the
  # staleness check in maybe_start_run - may call Settings.root_proxy_for or
  # Settings.refresh_data for this feature. Never read the whole shared root
  # into a local Hash, mutate multiple characters' branches, and save it
  # back - that reintroduces the exact lost-update race this whole approach
  # exists to avoid.

  # What this character is actively claiming right now, if anything - mirrors
  # @transporting / process_obstacle_queue's current obstacle pick. Returns
  # nil when nothing is claimed (teammates should not treat absence as
  # "claim cleared instantly" - they age out stale claims via
  # remote_claim_fresh?/SYNC_CLAIM_TTL_SECONDS instead, in case this
  # character's process died mid-claim without ever publishing the clear).
  def self.current_claim_snapshot
    if @transporting
      { kind: :transport, descriptor: @transporting[:descriptor], room: @piece_location[@transporting[:descriptor]] }
    elsif @phase == :clearing_obstacles && @obstacle_rooms.any?
      # @current_operation flips to :destroying_obstacle only transiently
      # inside destroy_obstacle itself - not durable enough to read back
      # from here. @phase/@obstacle_rooms.first stays stable for as long
      # as this obstacle room is actually the one being worked.
      { kind: :obstacle, room: @obstacle_rooms.first }
    end
  end

  def self.sync_publish_local_state!(force: false)
    return unless @sync_scope_for_run

    now = Time.now
    return if !force && !@sync_dirty
    return if !force && @last_sync_publish_at && (now - @last_sync_publish_at) < SYNC_THROTTLE_SECONDS

    @last_sync_publish_at = now
    @sync_dirty = false

    shared = Settings.root_proxy_for(@sync_scope_for_run)
    shared['slices'] ||= {}
    shared['slices'][Char.name] = {
      updated_at: now.to_i,
      edges: @edges.each_with_object({}) { |(k, v), h| h[k] = v },
      obstacle_rooms: @obstacle_rooms.dup,
      cleared_obstacle_rooms: @recently_cleared_obstacles.dup,
      trap_rooms: @trap_rooms.dup,
      cleared_trap_rooms: @recently_cleared_traps.dup,
      needed: @needed.dup,
      piece_location: @piece_location.dup,
      piece_updated_at: @piece_last_updated_at.dup,
      seen: @seen.dup,
      claim: current_claim_snapshot,
    }
  rescue StandardError => e
    debug_say "group sync: publish failed (#{e.class}: #{e.message}) - continuing solo this tick"
  end

  # Called once, from maybe_end_run, right as a run actually ends. Writes
  # nil to this character's own leaf under shared['slices'] rather than
  # deleting the key outright - same single-leaf-write shape as
  # sync_publish_local_state!'s normal publish (race-safe against a
  # teammate's own concurrent write to *their* leaf), and
  # sync_merge_remote_state! already skips a nil slice (`next if ...
  # slice.nil?`), so readers treat it identically to "never published."
  def self.clear_sync_state_for_completed_run!
    return unless group_sync_enabled? && @sync_scope_for_run

    shared = Settings.root_proxy_for(@sync_scope_for_run)
    shared['slices'] ||= {}
    shared['slices'][Char.name] = nil
  rescue StandardError => e
    debug_say "group sync: failed clearing this run's published state (#{e.class}: #{e.message})"
  end

  # Bypasses the throttle/dirty-flag gate for claim-worthy events (a piece
  # just became located, a transport/obstacle claim just started or
  # cleared) - teammates should see these promptly, not wait up to
  # SYNC_THROTTLE_SECONDS.
  #
  # Deliberately defers rather than calling sync_publish_local_state!
  # directly: observe_descriptor (and therefore this) can be reached from
  # install_listener's DownstreamHook proc, which runs on the socket-
  # reading thread, not this script's own thread - confirmed in the field,
  # this caused the *entire client* to freeze for minutes at a time
  # whenever a real Settings DB write here happened to contend with the
  # other character's process (SQLite's busy_timeout blocks synchronously
  # for up to 5s per attempt, on whatever thread called it). Just flag it
  # here; tick's own ensure block (always on this script's own thread)
  # is the only place that ever actually performs the write.
  def self.force_sync_publish!
    @sync_dirty = true
    @sync_force_pending = true
  end

  def self.merge_remote_edges!(remote_edges)
    return false unless remote_edges.is_a?(Hash)

    changed = false
    remote_edges.each do |from_uid, dirs|
      next unless dirs.is_a?(Hash)

      dirs.each do |dir, to_uid|
        next if @edges[from_uid].key?(dir) # fill-only - never overwrite a local entry

        @edges[from_uid][dir] = to_uid
        changed = true
      end
    end
    changed
  end

  # Thrown away and rebuilt from scratch rather than hand-grafting a
  # teammate's breadcrumb tree onto ours - much more robust given this
  # maze's confirmed cycles/non-reciprocal exits. Built into a fresh local
  # hash, then swapped in with one atomic assignment - never mutated
  # key-by-key mid-rebuild. Only ever called from tick's own quiescent top
  # (see sync_merge_remote_state!), never mid-navigation.
  def self.rebuild_parent_from_edges!
    return unless @guide_room_id

    new_parent = { @guide_room_id => { from: nil, back: nil } }
    queue = [@guide_room_id]
    until queue.empty?
      current = queue.shift
      @edges[current].each_value do |neighbor|
        next if new_parent.key?(neighbor)

        # Real reverse-edge lookup, never reverse_direction(dir) - this
        # maze has confirmed non-reciprocal exits (see StuckMove). Mirrors
        # reroot_tree's existing use of find_direction. Left nil if no
        # reverse edge is known, same as every other @parent[:back] miss
        # elsewhere in this file - never a crash.
        back = find_direction(neighbor, current)
        new_parent[neighbor] = { from: current, back: back }
        queue << neighbor
      end
    end

    @parent = new_parent
  end

  def self.merge_remote_obstacles!(slice)
    remote_pending = slice[:obstacle_rooms] || slice['obstacle_rooms']
    remote_cleared = slice[:cleared_obstacle_rooms] || slice['cleared_obstacle_rooms']

    @obstacle_rooms |= remote_pending if remote_pending.is_a?(Array)
    @obstacle_rooms -= remote_cleared if remote_cleared.is_a?(Array)
  end

  # Same union/subtract shape as merge_remote_obstacles! - a teammate's
  # known trap room is fill-only (never dropped just because their own
  # publish doesn't mention it - they may simply never have revisited it),
  # only actually removed once either character's own handle_traps
  # personally confirms it's gone.
  def self.merge_remote_trap_rooms!(slice)
    remote_pending = slice[:trap_rooms] || slice['trap_rooms']
    remote_cleared = slice[:cleared_trap_rooms] || slice['cleared_trap_rooms']

    @trap_rooms |= remote_pending if remote_pending.is_a?(Array)
    @trap_rooms -= remote_cleared if remote_cleared.is_a?(Array)
  end

  # :delivered always wins; adopt a teammate's :located info if we only
  # have :needed; keep ours if we already know more than they do; "newer
  # timestamp wins" when both have conflicting :located info. A teammate's
  # :in_transit is deliberately downgraded to :located here, never adopted
  # verbatim - :in_transit only means something paired with THAT
  # character's own @transporting. Their in-progress claim is represented
  # separately via merge_remote_claim! (with its own TTL), so a dead/
  # disconnected teammate's claim ages out instead of permanently hiding a
  # piece behind a status nothing will ever clear.
  def self.merge_remote_pieces!(slice)
    remote_needed   = slice[:needed] || slice['needed'] || {}
    remote_location = slice[:piece_location] || slice['piece_location'] || {}
    remote_seen     = slice[:seen] || slice['seen'] || {}
    remote_stamps   = slice[:piece_updated_at] || slice['piece_updated_at'] || {}

    remote_needed.each do |descriptor, remote_status|
      local_status = @needed[descriptor]

      if remote_status == :delivered
        @needed[descriptor] = :delivered
        next
      end
      next if local_status == :delivered

      if local_status.nil? || local_status == :needed
        if [:located, :in_transit, :claimed].include?(remote_status)
          remote_uid = remote_location[descriptor]
          rejected = @rejected_locations[descriptor]
          # Refuse to re-adopt the exact same descriptor+room we just
          # personally confirmed empty (continue_transport's "lost track"
          # path) until REJECTED_LOCATION_COOLDOWN_SECONDS passes - without
          # this, a teammate's still-stale slice re-asserts the same bad
          # location every merge, and local_status flips :needed -> :located
          # -> :needed forever with no fput/move/pause anywhere in the loop
          # to ever yield. A genuinely different remote_uid still goes
          # through normally - this only blocks the identical stale claim.
          stale_rejection = rejected && remote_uid && rejected[:uid] == remote_uid &&
                             (Time.now.to_i - rejected[:at]) < REJECTED_LOCATION_COOLDOWN_SECONDS
          unless stale_rejection
            @needed[descriptor] = remote_status == :in_transit ? :located : remote_status
            if remote_uid
              @piece_location[descriptor] = remote_uid
              @piece_last_updated_at[descriptor] = remote_stamps[descriptor] || Time.now.to_i
            end
          end
        end
      elsif local_status == :located && remote_status == :located
        local_at = @piece_last_updated_at[descriptor] || 0
        remote_at = remote_stamps[descriptor] || 0
        if remote_at > local_at && remote_location[descriptor]
          @piece_location[descriptor] = remote_location[descriptor]
          @piece_last_updated_at[descriptor] = remote_at
        end
      end
      # local_status == :located/:in_transit and remote is :needed/nothing -> keep ours, no-op.
    end

    remote_seen.each { |descriptor, uid| @seen[descriptor] = uid unless @seen.key?(descriptor) }
  end

  # Confirmed in the field: this used to just `return` whenever a
  # teammate's current claim was nil, leaving their PREVIOUS claim sitting
  # in @remote_claims untouched - so the moment they delivered/abandoned a
  # piece, everyone else kept treating it as actively claimed for up to a
  # full SYNC_CLAIM_TTL_SECONDS (90s) anyway, purely because nothing ever
  # told the entry to go away early. @remote_claims_by_char remembers each
  # teammate's last claim key so it can be actively dropped the instant
  # their own publish stops reasserting it, rather than only ever expiring
  # by elapsed time.
  def self.merge_remote_claim!(char_name, claim, claimed_at)
    new_key = claim.is_a?(Hash) ? (claim[:kind] == :transport ? claim[:descriptor] : claim[:room]) : nil

    previous_key = @remote_claims_by_char[char_name]
    if previous_key && previous_key != new_key
      entry = @remote_claims[previous_key]
      @remote_claims.delete(previous_key) if entry && entry[:char] == char_name
    end
    @remote_claims_by_char[char_name] = new_key

    return unless new_key

    @remote_claims[new_key] = { kind: claim[:kind], char: char_name, room: claim[:room], at: claimed_at || Time.now.to_i }
  end

  # Used by next_located_descriptor/maybe_abandon_for_closer_piece/
  # process_obstacle_queue to skip anything a teammate is actively working
  # on. A stale (process died, or silently abandoned without publishing
  # the clear) claim ages out on its own past SYNC_CLAIM_TTL_SECONDS rather
  # than needing an explicit removal path.
  def self.remote_claim_fresh?(key)
    claim = @remote_claims[key]
    return false unless claim

    (Time.now.to_i - claim[:at].to_i) < SYNC_CLAIM_TTL_SECONDS
  end

  def self.sync_merge_remote_state!
    return unless @sync_scope_for_run

    Settings.refresh_data(@sync_scope_for_run)
    shared = Settings.root_proxy_for(@sync_scope_for_run)
    slices = shared['slices'] || {}

    edges_changed = false
    slices.each do |char_name, slice|
      next if char_name == Char.name || slice.nil?

      edges_changed ||= merge_remote_edges!(slice[:edges] || slice['edges'])
      merge_remote_obstacles!(slice)
      merge_remote_trap_rooms!(slice)
      merge_remote_pieces!(slice)
      merge_remote_claim!(char_name, slice[:claim] || slice['claim'], slice[:updated_at] || slice['updated_at'])
    end

    rebuild_parent_from_edges! if edges_changed

    # Confirmed in the field: merge_remote_obstacles! can repopulate
    # @obstacle_rooms from a teammate's still-pending list well after this
    # character's own @fully_explored already flipped true (each side
    # reaches "nothing left to do" on its own schedule) - tick's dispatch
    # only ever calls process_obstacle_queue while !@fully_explored, so
    # without this, both characters ended up sitting in the idle branch
    # forever with a real, known block sitting unclaimed in @obstacle_rooms.
    # Same reopening as resweep_for_missed_obstacles! uses when it finds
    # something new.
    if @fully_explored && @obstacle_rooms.any?
      debug_say "group sync: teammate published obstacle room(s) we hadn't accounted for - resuming obstacle-clearing"
      @phase = :clearing_obstacles
      @fully_explored = false
    end
  rescue StandardError => e
    debug_say "group sync: merge failed (#{e.class}: #{e.message}) - continuing on local state only this tick"
  end
end

INQUICONUNDRUM_HELP = <<~HELP
  ============================================================
   InquiConundrum - Zephyra Wilds Conundrum automation
  ============================================================

   Usage:
     ;inquiconundrum                  Run it (always run this way - no inline options)
     ;inquiconundrum set              Show current options
     ;inquiconundrum help             Show this message
     ;inquiconundrum status           Report progress on the run in progress
     ;inquiconundrum reset            Walk back to the guide, report status,
                                       wait 5 seconds, then re-ask the guide
                                       for its current list of needed pieces
     ;inquiconundrum blocks           Drop whatever's in progress and focus
                                       on finding/destroying room blocks
                                       (vines, wards, walls) until a new
                                       part turns up, then resume normally
     ;inquiconundrum return           Drop whatever's in progress and kick
                                       a different known part home instead.
                                       "CANNOT OBEY - I don't know where a
                                       part is!" if nothing is located at
                                       all, or "CANNOT OBEY - This is the
                                       only part I know!" if the one just
                                       dropped is the only located piece

   set/help/status/reset/blocks/return all work even while a run is active
   EX: ;inqui set option=state, ;inqui help, ;inqui status, ;inqui reset

   Setting options:
     ;inquiconundrum set option=value option=value
     ;inquiconundrum set destroytraps=true debug=true

   Options (persist until changed):
     destroytraps   Always kill bone-spike/tendril traps on sight.
     debug          Extra diagnostic messages - room ids, why exploration
                     branched the way it did, kick results, pause causes.
                     Turn this on if the script ever pauses or stalls and
                     you're not sure why.
     repeatevent    When a run ends, automatically stow hands, get the
                     package, stow hands again, gird, and walk back to the
                     Arena Magister to ask for entry again, queuing up the
                     next run without you lifting a finger. Reports
                     "Completed run - # total completions" each time. When
                     off (default), the script stops dead in the
                     post-ejection room and pause_scripts itself - it never
                     walks back toward the arena on its own; resume with
                     ;unpause inquiconundrum when you're ready to go again.
                     If grouped, only the group leader walks back - everyone
                     else "join"s the leader first so they're dragged along,
                     instead of each character go2-ing back independently.
     surrendermania When the guide says you've passed the threshold for
                     winning a prize if you surrender (even though the
                     contest isn't concluded), surrender twice and treat
                     the run as over immediately - same as winning. Off by
                     default.
     pacifist       Avoid all combat. A kick rejected as "too dangerous"
                     abandons that piece (remembers where it is, tries
                     something else, comes back to it later) instead of
                     pausing for you to clear the room. An obstacle room
                     with a hostile in it gets skipped for another logged
                     obstacle the same way. If every located piece is
                     blocked by a monster AND at least 4 pieces have been
                     announced so far, it gives up avoiding and pushes
                     through one of them rather than stall forever -
                     below 4 announced, it explores/clears obstacles
                     instead, since there's likely still an unblocked
                     piece to find. A blocked piece gets a normal (non-
                     combat) retry attempt again every minute - the
                     monster that blocked it might be long gone - and
                     overrides whatever's currently happening (exploring,
                     destroying an obstacle, or pushing a different piece)
                     if it's actually closer to the guide than wherever
                     you currently are; otherwise it just waits its turn
                     normally. The same all-blocked rule applies to
                     obstacles regardless of how many pieces are known.
                     Off by default.
   Freely traversed rooms explored first, Then

   Vines and thornbound wards are destroyed to reveal sealed off a rooms with needed parts.

   If another player is found in the same room as a part being pushed, it's
   assumed claimed by them - the script abandons it and moves on to another
   part, exploration, or obstacle clearing instead of racing them for it.

   If you're grouped with another character also running this script, they
   automatically share discovered rooms, parts, and obstacles with each
   other (no setup needed) - whoever finds something first benefits both,
   and a part/obstacle one of you is actively working is skipped by the
   other instead of being duplicated.

   Combat is left to you, and only ever comes up when moving a part home.
   The only time it pauses is when a kick is rejected as "too dangerous" 
   while pushing a found piece home. Kill whatever's blocking
   the kick, then resume with ;u.

   The script idles until you're placed anywhere in the zone (Mistwarden
   Temple or Zephyra Wilds), then takes over automatically. Stop it with
   ;exit inquiconundrum or ;kill inquiconundrum.
  ============================================================
HELP

# --- Entry point ---

args = Script.current.vars[1..-1] || []

if args[0] =~ /^help$/i
  InquiConundrum.show_settings
  respond(INQUICONUNDRUM_HELP)
  exit
end

if args[0] =~ /^set$/i
  InquiConundrum.handle_set(args[1..-1] || [])
  exit
end

# Only reachable here when no instance is already running - the upstream
# hook installed below intercepts ";inquiconundrum status"/";inqui status"
# (and set/help/reset) before Lich's own dispatch ever sees it whenever one
# is.
if args[0] =~ /^status$/i
  InquiConundrum.report_status_now
  exit
end

if args[0] =~ /^reset$/i
  InquiConundrum.handle_reset
  exit
end

InquiConundrum.install_listener
InquiConundrum.install_upstream_hook

# One-shot, ~3s-bounded - satisfies Group.members' own maybe_check so
# group_sync_enabled? never has to trigger a blocking re-check mid-tick
# later. Group::Observer keeps the roster live off game output afterward.
Group.check rescue nil

InquiConundrum.check_database_health

before_dying do
  InquiConundrum.remove_listener
  InquiConundrum.remove_upstream_hook
end

respond("InquiConundrum is running!")
InquiConundrum.main_loop
